# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Abstract Class (KTU 2024 Definition):**
> An **abstract class** in Java is a class that is declared using the `abstract` keyword and is characterized by the fact that **it cannot be instantiated directly** (i.e., objects of an abstract class cannot be created using the `new` keyword). It serves as a *blueprint* or *partial implementation* for other classes and **may contain zero or more abstract methods** (methods declared but not implemented) along with concrete methods, instance variables, constructors, and static members.

In the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus for **Object Oriented Programming (PECIT633)**, abstract classes form the conceptual bridge between **generalization** (common behavior) and **specialization** (unique behavior), forming a critical pillar of polymorphism and inheritance.

### 1.1.1 Syntax Declaration

```java
abstract class ClassName {
    // Instance variables
    // Concrete (implemented) methods
    // Abstract (unimplemented) methods
    abstract returnType methodName(parameters);
}
```

The keyword **`abstract`** is a **non-access modifier** in Java, used exclusively for classes and methods.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy & Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy — The "Vehicle Registration Form":**
> Imagine a government *Vehicle Registration Template*. The template has:
> - **Fixed (concrete) fields** — Vehicle Number, Owner Name, Registration Date
> - **Blank (abstract) fields** — "Type of Vehicle" (Car, Bike, Truck...) — *each subclass must fill this in its own way*
>
> You **cannot submit the blank template itself** for registration — it must be **completed by a specific vehicle category** (Car Registration, Bike Registration, etc.). The template is the **abstract class**, and each completed form is a **concrete subclass**.

**Another simple analogy:** Think of an **Architect's Master Blueprint** for a housing colony.
- The blueprint defines the **foundation, walls, and roof structure** (concrete parts).
- It leaves the **interior design and paint color** open (abstract parts).
- You cannot *move into* the blueprint itself — you must first build a specific **house** (concrete subclass) that fills in the abstract details.

---

## 1.3 Why Abstract Classes Exist — The OOP Motivation

> [!TIP]
> **KTU High-Yield Insight:** Abstract classes enforce a **contract** on subclasses. They ensure that every subclass provides a specific behavior, while allowing shared code reuse in the parent. This is the **OOP principle of "Program to an Interface/Abstract Superclass, not to a Concrete Implementation"**.

**Three core purposes** of an abstract class:

| # | Purpose | KTU-Style Explanation |
|---|---------|------------------------|
| 1 | **Enforce a contract** | Forces subclasses to implement specific methods |
| 2 | **Promote code reuse** | Common code lives once in the abstract class |
| 3 | **Achieve polymorphism** | Parent reference can point to any subclass object |

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Misconception:** A class is **NOT** abstract simply because it has abstract methods. A class is abstract *only if* it is **declared** with the `abstract` keyword. However, a class **must** be declared abstract if it contains even **one** abstract method.
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Rules

## 2.1 The Five Golden Rules of Abstract Classes (KTU Board-Exam Favorite)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule #1 — No Instantiation:**
> You **cannot** create an object of an abstract class using `new`. The compiler will throw an error.
> ```java
> abstract class Shape { }
> // Shape s = new Shape();   // ❌ Compile-time error
> ```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule #2 — Mandatory `abstract` Keyword on Incomplete Methods:**
> Any method that has only a **declaration (signature)** and **no body** must be marked `abstract`. Abstract methods have **no curly braces** — they end with a **semicolon**.
> ```java
> abstract double area();      // ✅ Valid abstract method
> abstract double area() { }   // ❌ Invalid — body not allowed
> ```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule #3 — Subclass Must Implement ALL Abstract Methods:**
> The **first concrete subclass** (i.e., a non-abstract class extending the abstract class) **must override and implement every abstract method** inherited from the parent. Otherwise, that subclass must itself be declared `abstract`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule #4 — Abstract Classes Can Have EVERYTHING a Normal Class Has:**
> An abstract class **may contain**:
> - Instance variables
> - Concrete (fully implemented) methods
> - Constructors (called via `super()` from subclass)
> - `static` methods and `static` fields
> - `final` methods (cannot be overridden)
> - Other abstract methods
>
> The **only thing it cannot have** is being **instantiated directly**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rule #5 — Abstract Class Cannot Be `final`:**
> A class cannot be both `abstract` and `final` because `abstract` requires the class to be **extended**, while `final` **prevents extension**. This is a **compile-time contradiction**.

---

## 2.2 Abstract Class vs Concrete Class — Comparative Matrix

| Property | Abstract Class | Concrete Class |
|----------|----------------|----------------|
| Declaration | `abstract class` | `class` (no `abstract`) |
| Instantiation (`new`) | ❌ Not allowed | ✅ Allowed |
| Abstract methods | ✅ May contain | ❌ Cannot contain |
| Concrete methods | ✅ May contain | ✅ May contain |
| Constructors | ✅ May contain | ✅ May contain |
| `static` members | ✅ Allowed | ✅ Allowed |
| Can be `final`? | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Can be inherited? | ✅ Yes (its purpose) | ✅ Yes |
| Can be `super` reference? | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |

---

## 2.3 Abstract Class vs Interface (Conceptual Foundation)

> [!NOTE]
> In KTU 2024, this is a **favourite 7-mark question**. Although the full interface comparison is in Module 2, the foundation must be set here.

| Feature | Abstract Class | Interface |
|---------|----------------|-----------|
| Keyword | `abstract class` | `interface` |
| Methods | Concrete + Abstract | Abstract (default since Java 8 also has default/static) |
| Variables | Any type | `public static final` only |
| Inheritance | `extends` (single) | `implements` (multiple allowed) |
| Constructors | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Access modifiers | Any | `public` only (pre-Java 9) |
| When to use | "IS-A" with shared code | "CAN-DO" capability contract |

---

## 2.4 Abstract Methods — The Contract Mechanism

An **abstract method** is a method signature **without a body**. Its purpose is to **declare a behavior** that every subclass **must provide its own implementation** for.

### Formal Definition

An abstract method has:
- The modifier **`abstract`**
- A **return type**
- A **method name**
- A **parameter list (parentheses mandatory)**
- A **semicolon** (no curly braces, no body)

### Example Declaration

```java
abstract class BankAccount {
    double balance;

    // Concrete method
    void deposit(double amount) {
        balance += amount;
    }

    // Abstract method — NO body, ends with semicolon
    abstract double calculateInterest();
}
```

---

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

> [!TIP]
> **Where abstract classes shine in industry:**
> - **JDBC API** — `DriverManager`, `Connection`, `Statement` are interfaces/abstract bases.
> - **Spring Framework** — Abstract `Controller` classes.
> - **GUI Frameworks** — `JFrame`, `Applet` (legacy) define templates.
> - **Game Development** — `Sprite` abstract class with abstract `render()` method.
> - **Template Method Design Pattern** — built directly on abstract classes.

---

## 2.6 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> **Quick-Reference Summary Table — Abstract Class**

| Concept | Truth Value / Syntax | Notes |
|---------|----------------------|-------|
| Declaration syntax | `abstract class Name { }` | Required keyword |
| Can we use `new`? | **NO** | Compile-time error |
| Can have abstract method? | **YES** | At least zero, no upper limit |
| Can have concrete method? | **YES** | Full implementation |
| Subclass responsibility | **Implement all abstract methods** OR be declared `abstract` | No shortcuts |
| Can have constructor? | **YES** | Called via `super()` |
| Can have `main()`? | **YES** | Can be invoked normally |
| Can be `final`? | **NO** | Logical contradiction |
| Can be `static`? | **NO** (outer class) | Inner classes can be `static` |
| Can abstract method be `static`? | **NO** | `static` cannot be overridden |
| Can abstract method be `final`? | **NO** | `final` prevents overriding |
| Can abstract method be `private`? | **NO** | Subclass must see it to override |
| Abstract class can extend concrete class? | **YES** | Inherits the concrete implementation |
| Concrete class can extend abstract class? | **YES** | Must implement all abstract methods |
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# Section 3: Step-by-Step Examples, Code Analysis & Implementation

## 3.1 Worked Example #1 — The "Shape" Hierarchy (Classic KTU Question)

> [!NOTE]
> This is the **most frequently asked abstract class question** in KTU university exams. Master this pattern.

### Step 1: Define the Abstract Parent

```java
// File: Shape.java
abstract class Shape {
    String color;

    // Concrete (implemented) constructor
    Shape(String color) {
        this.color = color;
        System.out.println("Shape constructor called. Color: " + color);
    }

    // Concrete method — shared by all shapes
    String getColor() {
        return color;
    }

    // Abstract methods — must be implemented by subclasses
    abstract double area();
    abstract double perimeter();
}
```

**Explanation of Step 1:**
- `Shape` is declared `abstract` because it has two abstract methods.
- A concrete `getColor()` method is provided — **reusability** for all subclasses.
- The `Shape(String color)` constructor is called via `super()` from subclasses.

---

### Step 2: Create Concrete Subclass `Circle`

```java
// File: Circle.java
class Circle extends Shape {
    double radius;

    Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);             // calls Shape(String color)
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    // Implementation of abstract method area() — REQUIRED
    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }

    // Implementation of abstract method perimeter() — REQUIRED
    @Override
    double perimeter() {
        return 2 * Math.PI * radius;
    }
}
```

**Explanation of Step 2:**
- `@Override` annotation is a **compiler-safety check** that the method actually overrides a parent method.
- If even **one** abstract method is not implemented, the compiler will force `Circle` to be declared `abstract` too.

---

### Step 3: Create Concrete Subclass `Rectangle`

```java
// File: Rectangle.java
class Rectangle extends Shape {
    double length, width;

    Rectangle(String color, double length, double width) {
        super(color);
        this.length = length;
        this.width  = width;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * width;
    }

    @Override
    double perimeter() {
        return 2 * (length + width);
    }
}
```

---

### Step 4: Polymorphic Driver Class

```java
// File: TestShape.java
public class TestShape {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Shape s = new Shape("Red");  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: cannot instantiate

        // Polymorphic references — parent type, child object
        Shape c = new Circle("Blue", 7.0);
        Shape r = new Rectangle("Green", 5.0, 3.0);

        System.out.println("Circle color: "   + c.getColor()
                         + ", area: "        + c.area()
                         + ", perimeter: "   + c.perimeter());

        System.out.println("Rectangle color: " + r.getColor()
                         + ", area: "        + r.area()
                         + ", perimeter: "   + r.perimeter());
    }
}
```

---

### Step 5: Output Trace

```
Shape constructor called. Color: Blue
Shape constructor called. Color: Green
Circle color: Blue, area: 153.93804002589985, perimeter: 43.982297150257104
Rectangle color: Green, area: 15.0, perimeter: 16.0
```

> [!TIP]
> **Why two "Shape constructor called" lines?**
> Because both `Circle` and `Rectangle` call `super(color)` which invokes the parent constructor. This proves the **constructor of an abstract class IS executed**, even though the abstract class itself is never directly instantiated.

---

## 3.2 Worked Example #2 — Partial Implementation (Abstract Subclass)

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 7-Mark Hot Topic:** A subclass may also be declared abstract if it does **not implement all** abstract methods of its parent.

```java
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void sound();
    abstract void move();
}

// Dog implements sound() but not move() → must be abstract
abstract class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
    // move() NOT implemented → Dog remains abstract
}

// Puppy finally implements both
class Puppy extends Dog {
    @Override
    void move() {
        System.out.println("Puppy runs on four legs");
    }
}
```

**Analysis:**
- `Animal` — 2 abstract methods, fully abstract.
- `Dog` — implements 1 of 2, so it must also be `abstract`.
- `Puppy` — implements the final missing `move()`, so it is **concrete** and can be instantiated.

---

## 3.3 Worked Example #3 — Abstract Class Implementing a Contract via Object Array (Polymorphism)

```java
abstract class Employee {
    String name;
    Employee(String n) { name = n; }
    abstract double calculateSalary();
}

class FullTimeEmployee extends Employee {
    double monthly;
    FullTimeEmployee(String n, double m) { super(n); monthly = m; }
    @Override double calculateSalary() { return monthly; }
}

class PartTimeEmployee extends Employee {
    double hourlyRate, hours;
    PartTimeEmployee(String n, double r, double h) {
        super(n); hourlyRate = r; hours = h;
    }
    @Override double calculateSalary() { return hourlyRate * hours; }
}

public class Payroll {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee[] staff = {
            new FullTimeEmployee("Anu",  50000),
            new PartTimeEmployee("Binu", 500, 40)
        };

        double total = 0;
        for (Employee e : staff) {
            total += e.calculateSalary();   // dynamic dispatch
            System.out.println(e.name + " earns " + e.calculateSalary());
        }
        System.out.println("Total payroll: " + total);
    }
}
```

### Output

```
Anu earns 50000.0
Binu earns 20000.0
Total payroll: 70000.0
```

**Key Insight — Runtime Polymorphism:**
At compile time, the JVM only knows the reference is of type `Employee`. At **runtime**, the JVM dispatches the call to the **actual object's overridden method** — this is **dynamic method dispatch**, a direct consequence of using abstract classes.

---

## 3.4 Step-by-Step Compilation Analysis

> [!WARNING]
> **Why `Shape s = new Shape(...)` fails at compile time:**

**Step A:** The Java compiler reads the source code.
**Step B:** It encounters `new Shape("Red")`.
**Step C:** It checks the class declaration of `Shape`.
**Step D:** It finds the `abstract` keyword.
**Step E:** Compiler rule: *"If a class is abstract, the `new` operator is forbidden."*
**Step F:** Compiler immediately emits:
```
error: Shape is abstract; cannot be instantiated
```
**Step G:** Compilation halts — `.class` file is **not** generated.

This is a **static (compile-time) check**, not a runtime error. The program never runs.

---

## 3.5 Constructor Chaining in Abstract Classes — Step Trace

```java
abstract class A {
    A() { System.out.println("A()"); }
}
class B extends A {
    B() { System.out.println("B()"); }
}
class C extends B {
    C() { System.out.println("C()"); }
}
```

When `new C()` is executed, the output is:

```
A()
B()
C()
```

**Why?**
1. `new C()` invokes `C()`.
2. The first line of `C()` is an **implicit** `super()` call → invokes `B()`.
3. The first line of `B()` is an implicit `super()` call → invokes `A()`.
4. `A()` runs and prints `"A()"`.
5. Control returns to `B()`, prints `"B()"`.
6. Control returns to `C()`, prints `"C()"`.

> [!TIP]
> **KTU 3-Mark Favourite:** *"What is the output of the following code involving abstract classes?"* — Always trace the **constructor chain** from the **most-derived** class to the **root**.
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
# Section 4: Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Class Hierarchy — Shape Example

```mermaid
classDiagram
    direction LR
    classShapeAbs <<abstract>>
    classShape : String color
    classShape : +String getColor()
    classShape : +double area()
    classShape : +double perimeter()
    classShape : +Shape(String color)
    classShapeAbs : class Shape
    classCircle : -double radius
    classCircle : +Circle(String, double)
    classCircle : +double area()
    classCircle : +double perimeter()
    classRectangle : -double length
    classRectangle : -double width
    classRectangle : +Rectangle(String, double, double)
    classRectangle : +double area()
    classRectangle : +double perimeter()
    Shape <|-- Circle
    Shape <|-- Rectangle
```

**Reading the diagram:**
- `Shape` is the **abstract parent** (shown in italics by UML convention).
- `Circle` and `Rectangle` are **concrete subclasses** that **inherit** from `Shape`.
- The open-triangle arrow `<|--` denotes **inheritance** ("is-a" relationship).

---

## 4.2 Lifecycle of Object Creation Through an Abstract Reference

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Code: Shape s = new Circle Blue, 7.0] --> B{Is Shape abstract?}
    B -- YES, but we are NOT creating a Shape object --> C[Compiler allows parent reference]
    C --> D[Runtime: Memory allocated for Circle object]
    D --> E[Constructor Chain invoked]
    E --> F[Circle constructor calls super color]
    F --> G[Shape constructor executes]
    G --> H[Control returns to Circle constructor]
    H --> I[Circle fields initialized: radius = 7.0]
    I --> J[Object reference stored in variable s]
    J --> K[Call s.area - Dynamic Dispatch]
    K --> L{Actual object type?}
    L -- Circle --> M[Execute Circle.area]
    L -- Rectangle --> N[Execute Rectangle.area]
    M --> O[Return PI * r * r]
    N --> P[Return length * width]
```

---

## 4.3 Block Diagram — Abstract Class Internal Architecture

```mermaid
block-beta
    columns 1
    block:abstractClass["ABSTRACT CLASS : Shape"]
        columns 2
        block:instance["Instance Variables"]
            instanceFields["+ color : String"]
        end
        block:methods["Methods"]
            concreteMethod["+ getColor() : String  (Concrete)"]
            absArea["+ area() : double  (Abstract)"]
            absPeri["+ perimeter() : double  (Abstract)"]
        end
        block:constructor["Constructor"]
            ctor["+ Shape(String color)"]
        end
        block:accessBlock["Access Restrictions"]
            restrict["X Cannot use: new Shape(...)"]
        end
    end
```

**Interpretation:**
- The abstract class is a **complete unit** containing data, concrete behavior, abstract contracts, and constructors.
- The **only** missing piece is the **body of abstract methods** — provided by subclasses.

---

## 4.4 Decision Flow — What Happens When You Try to Instantiate

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Programmer writes: new Shape] --> B{Is Shape declared abstract?}
    B -- YES --> C[Compiler Error: Shape is abstract cannot be instantiated]
    B -- NO --> D[Object created successfully]
    C --> E[Compilation FAILS, .class file not produced]
    D --> F[Memory allocated, constructor invoked]
```
<!-- SECTION_4_END -->

<!-- SECTION_5_START -->
# Section 5: KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Question A1
**[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Model Question Paper]**
**Q: Define an abstract class in Java. Can we create an object of an abstract class? Justify your answer.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**
- **(1 Mark)** An abstract class in Java is a class declared with the `abstract` keyword. It may contain abstract methods (methods without a body) as well as concrete methods, instance variables, and constructors.
- **(1 Mark)** No, we **cannot** create an object of an abstract class directly using the `new` keyword.
- **(1 Mark)** Justification: The Java compiler forbids instantiation of abstract classes because an abstract class is considered **incomplete** — its abstract methods have no body. Allowing instantiation would lead to calls on methods with no implementation. However, we **can** create a reference variable of an abstract class type and use it to refer to subclass objects (polymorphism).

---

### Question A2
**[KTU University Exam — June 2024]**
**Q: What is the difference between an abstract class and a concrete class? Give one example of each.**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**
- **(1 Mark)** An **abstract class** is declared using the `abstract` keyword and cannot be instantiated. It may contain abstract methods without a body. Example: `abstract class Shape { abstract void draw(); }`
- **(1 Mark)** A **concrete class** is a regular class that has **no abstract methods** and can be instantiated directly using `new`. Example: `class Circle { void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing circle"); } }`
- **(1 Mark)** A concrete subclass that extends an abstract class **must provide implementations** for all inherited abstract methods, otherwise it must also be declared abstract.

---

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, Internal Choice)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Pattern:** Each Part B question has **internal choice**. You must answer **either** Question A **or** Question B. Each question has two sub-parts: **(a) 7 marks** and **(b) 7 marks**.

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)**
**[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Adapted]**

**(a)** Explain the concept of an abstract class in Java. List any **four** rules that must be followed when using abstract classes. (7 Marks)

**(b)** Write a Java program to create an abstract class `Vehicle` with an abstract method `speed()`. Create two subclasses `Car` and `Bike` that implement the `speed()` method. Demonstrate polymorphism using a common reference. (7 Marks)

#### Model Solution — (a)

**(2 Marks) Definition:**
An abstract class in Java is a class declared with the `abstract` keyword. It serves as a **partial implementation** and a **blueprint** for other classes. It may contain abstract methods (unimplemented) and concrete methods (implemented). Objects of an abstract class cannot be created directly.

**(5 Marks) Four Rules:**

1. **No Instantiation:** An abstract class cannot be instantiated using `new`. The compiler will throw an error such as `error: Vehicle is abstract; cannot be instantiated`.

2. **Subclass Obligation:** The first concrete subclass of an abstract class must provide implementations for **all** abstract methods of the parent. If it does not, the subclass must also be declared `abstract`.

3. **Constructors Allowed:** Abstract classes can have constructors, but these are invoked **indirectly** through `super()` calls from subclass constructors. This ensures instance variables of the abstract class are properly initialized.

4. **Cannot Be Final:** A class cannot be both `abstract` and `final` because the two modifiers are logically contradictory — `abstract` requires extension, while `final` prevents it. (Additionally, abstract methods cannot be `static`, `final`, or `private`.)

#### Model Solution — (b)

**Complete Java Program (7 Marks):**

```java
// File: Vehicle.java
abstract class Vehicle {
    String brand;
    Vehicle(String brand) {
        this.brand = brand;
    }
    abstract void speed();        // abstract method

    void displayBrand() {         // concrete method
        System.out.println("Brand: " + brand);
    }
}

// File: Car.java
class Car extends Vehicle {
    Car(String brand) { super(brand); }

    @Override
    void speed() {
        System.out.println("Car speed: 180 km/h");
    }
}

// File: Bike.java
class Bike extends Vehicle {
    Bike(String brand) { super(brand); }

    @Override
    void speed() {
        System.out.println("Bike speed: 100 km/h");
    }
}

// File: TestVehicle.java
public class TestVehicle {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vehicle v1 = new Car("Toyota");
        Vehicle v2 = new Bike("Yamaha");

        v1.displayBrand();
        v1.speed();

        v2.displayBrand();
        v2.speed();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Brand: Toyota
Car speed: 180 km/h
Brand: Yamaha
Bike speed: 100 km/h
```

**Explanation of Polymorphism (carry to full marks):**
- The reference `v1` is of type `Vehicle` (abstract), but it points to a `Car` object.
- When `v1.speed()` is called, **dynamic method dispatch** causes the JVM to invoke `Car.speed()` at runtime, not `Vehicle.speed()`.
- This is the **runtime polymorphism** that abstract classes enable.

---

### **Question B (14 Marks — Alternative Choice)**
**[KTU University Exam — June 2024, Model Paper]**

**(a)** What happens if a subclass does not implement all the abstract methods of its parent class? Explain with an example. (7 Marks)

**(b)** Design an abstract class `BankAccount` with fields `accountNumber`, `balance`, and abstract method `calculateInterest()`. Derive two classes `SavingsAccount` (interest rate 4%) and `CurrentAccount` (interest rate 2%) that implement `calculateInterest()`. Write a main class to demonstrate the working. (7 Marks)

#### Model Solution — (a)

**(3 Marks) Explanation:**
If a subclass inherits abstract methods from its abstract parent but does **not** provide implementations for **all** of them, then the subclass must itself be declared `abstract`. Otherwise, the compiler will raise an error:
```
error: ClassName is not abstract and does not override abstract method methodName() in ParentClass
```

The chain of abstraction can continue through multiple levels — a class only becomes **concrete** (and thus instantiable) when **every** abstract method in its inheritance chain has been implemented.

**(4 Marks) Example:**

```java
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void sound();
    abstract void eat();
}

// Cat implements sound() but NOT eat() → must be abstract
abstract class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Meow");
    }
    // eat() not implemented → Cat is abstract
}

// PersianCat finally implements eat() → becomes concrete
class PersianCat extends Cat {
    @Override
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Persian cat eats fish");
    }
}
```

- `Animal` has two abstract methods.
- `Cat` implements only `sound()` → remains abstract.
- `PersianCat` implements `eat()` → becomes a **concrete instantiable** class.
- Attempting `new Cat()` will fail with a compile-time error.

#### Model Solution — (b)

**Complete Java Program (7 Marks):**

```java
// Abstract class
abstract class BankAccount {
    String accountNumber;
    double balance;

    BankAccount(String accountNumber, double balance) {
        this.accountNumber = accountNumber;
        this.balance = balance;
    }

    abstract double calculateInterest();

    void displayDetails() {
        System.out.println("Account: " + accountNumber
                         + ", Balance: " + balance
                         + ", Interest: " + calculateInterest());
    }
}

// SavingsAccount subclass
class SavingsAccount extends BankAccount {
    SavingsAccount(String accNo, double bal) {
        super(accNo, bal);
    }
    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return balance * 0.04;   // 4% interest
    }
}

// CurrentAccount subclass
class CurrentAccount extends BankAccount {
    CurrentAccount(String accNo, double bal) {
        super(accNo, bal);
    }
    @Override
    double calculateInterest() {
        return balance * 0.02;   // 2% interest
    }
}

// Main class
public class BankDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        BankAccount s = new SavingsAccount("SA001", 100000);
        BankAccount c = new CurrentAccount("CA001", 200000);

        s.displayDetails();
        c.displayDetails();
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Account: SA001, Balance: 100000.0, Interest: 4000.0
Account: CA001, Balance: 200000.0, Interest: 4000.0
```

**Working Explanation:**
- `BankAccount` is abstract; it declares the contract `calculateInterest()`.
- `SavingsAccount` and `CurrentAccount` provide different implementations (4% and 2%).
- The reference `s` and `c` are of type `BankAccount`, but at runtime, the correct `calculateInterest()` is invoked.
- The concrete `displayDetails()` method in the parent uses the polymorphic call to `calculateInterest()`, showing **runtime polymorphism in action**.

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls Where Students Lose Marks:**
>
> 1. **Forgetting `@Override` annotation** — Loses **0.5 to 1 mark** in code questions. Always use it for clarity and safety.
> 2. **Forgetting `super()` call in subclass constructor** — If the parent has no default (no-arg) constructor, this causes a **compile-time error** that students miss. Always pass parameters explicitly to `super(...)`.
> 3. **Trying to instantiate an abstract class in `main()`** — A common student mistake is `Shape s = new Shape();` inside a demo program. This causes compilation to fail and **no marks** are awarded for the program.
> 4. **Leaving abstract methods unimplemented in the "concrete" subclass** — The student writes `class Circle extends Shape` but forgets to define `area()`. The compiler will reject it, and the entire program carries **zero** execution marks.
> 5. **Confusing abstract class with interface** — Do not write `implements Shape` — it should be `extends Shape`. Interfaces use `implements`; classes use `extends`. Mixing these costs marks.
> 6. **Not tracing the constructor chain in output-prediction questions** — A typical 3-mark question asks "What is the output?" involving abstract classes. Students forget the implicit `super()` call from the subclass to the abstract parent. **Always trace constructors from the bottom up.**
> 7. **Using `private` with abstract methods** — Compile error. Abstract methods must be visible to subclasses, so they cannot be `private`. Similarly, they cannot be `static` or `final`.

