## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!TIP]
> **High-Density Rapid-Revision Checklist — Abstract Classes**

- ✅ An **abstract class** is declared using the `abstract` keyword.
- ✅ It **cannot be instantiated** using `new`.
- ✅ It **may contain** abstract methods (no body) **and** concrete methods.
- ✅ The first concrete subclass **must implement all** abstract methods of the parent; otherwise, it must also be declared `abstract`.
- ✅ Abstract classes **can have constructors**, which are invoked through `super()` from subclasses.
- ✅ Abstract classes **can have `main()`** and can be run directly.
- ✅ Abstract classes **can have static, final, and instance variables**.
- ✅ An abstract class **cannot be `final`**, and an abstract method **cannot be `static`, `final`, or `private`**.
- ✅ Abstract classes support **runtime polymorphism** via dynamic method dispatch.
- ✅ A reference of an abstract class type **can hold a subclass object**.
- ✅ Use **abstract class** when classes share **code and contract** ("IS-A" with shared state/behavior).
- ✅ The **Template Method Design Pattern** is the canonical use case for abstract classes.
- ✅ In constructor chains, the **abstract parent's constructor runs first**, then the subclass constructor.
- ✅ KTU exam tip: When asked to "design a hierarchy," always start with the **abstract parent**, define **abstract methods for varying behavior**, and put **shared code as concrete methods** in the parent.

