# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Inner Classes — Operational Mechanics

### 2.1.1 Member Inner Class (Non-Static)

A **Member Inner Class** is declared at the member level of a class — just like fields and methods — but **without** the `static` modifier. Each instance of the inner class is **logically tied** to an instance of the outer class.

**Operational Rules (Why & How):**

- **Why it can't have `static` members (prior to JDK 16):** A non-static inner class requires an outer instance for context. Static members imply "class-level" independence, which contradicts this binding.
- **How instantiation works:** You **cannot** write `new Inner()` from a static context (e.g., `main`). You **must** write `outerObj.new Inner()`.
- **Outer reference:** Inside the inner class, `OuterClass.this` explicitly accesses the enclosing instance.

### 2.1.2 Static Nested Class

A **Static Nested Class** is declared with the `static` modifier. It is essentially a **top-level class** packaged inside another class for **namespace management**.

**Operational Rules:**

- **Why it's faster:** It doesn't carry an implicit reference to the outer instance, so it uses **less memory** and has **lower instantiation overhead**.
- **How instantiation works:** Simply `new Outer.StaticNested()` — no outer object needed.
- **Access restriction:** It can only access **static** members of the outer class directly. To access non-static members, you must explicitly create an outer object.

### 2.1.3 Local Inner Class

A **Local Inner Class** is declared inside a **method body**, **constructor**, or **initialization block**. Its scope is restricted to that block — it cannot be accessed outside.

**Operational Rules:**

- **Why it exists:** When a helper class is needed **only inside one method**, declaring it locally prevents namespace pollution.
- **Local variable capture:** It can access local variables of the enclosing method **only if they are `final` or *effectively final*** (i.e., not reassigned after declaration). This restriction exists because the inner class instance may outlive the method's stack frame, but local variables would be destroyed — Java copies them as synthetic captures.

### 2.1.4 Anonymous Inner Class

An **Anonymous Inner Class** is a class that is **declared and instantiated in a single expression** — it has no name. It is most commonly used to provide an inline implementation of an **interface** or **abstract class**.

**Operational Rules:**

- **Why it exists:** For one-off implementations (e.g., event handlers, `Runnable`, `Comparator`), creating a named class is overkill.
- **How it's written:** `new InterfaceName() { /* override methods */ };` or `new SuperClass(args) { /* override */ };`.
- **Limitation:** It can extend **only one** class or implement **only one** interface, and cannot declare constructors (it uses an implicit one).

---

## 2.2 Inheritance — Operational Mechanics

### 2.2.1 The `extends` Keyword and IS-A Test

Whenever a class `B extends A`, every `B` object **IS-A** `A`. This is not metaphor — it is a **compiler-enforced guarantee**. You can pass a `B` reference to any variable, parameter, or container typed as `A`.

### 2.2.2 Method Overriding vs. Method Overloading (KTU High-Yield Distinction)

> [!TIP]
> **Mnemonic:** **Override** = same **signature**, different **class (parent-child)**. **Overload** = different **signature**, same **class (or inheritance)**.

| Feature | Overriding | Overloading |
|---------|------------|-------------|
| Where | Parent & child class | Same class (or via inheritance) |
| Signature | **Exactly the same** | **Different** (params / order) |
| Return type | Same or **covariant** (subtype) | Can be anything |
| Binding | **Runtime** (dynamic dispatch) | **Compile-time** |
| Keyword | `@Override` (recommended) | N/A |
| Polymorphism Type | **Run-time polymorphism** | **Compile-time polymorphism** |

### 2.2.3 Constructor Chaining and `super()`

When a subclass object is created, Java executes a **chain of constructors** from the topmost superclass down to the subclass. This is called **constructor chaining**.

- **Rule 1:** If a constructor does **not** explicitly call `super(...)` or `this(...)`, the compiler **automatically inserts** `super();` (no-arg call) as the first statement.
- **Rule 2:** If the parent has **no default constructor** (because you've defined a parameterized one), and the child doesn't explicitly call `super(args)`, the program **will not compile**.

---

## 2.3 The `super` Keyword — Operational Mechanics

### 2.3.1 `super()` — Calling Parent Constructor

**Why use it?** To initialize inherited fields properly, especially when the parent has no default constructor or you need a specific initialization path.

**How it works:** Java matches the argument list against available parent constructors. If no match is found, **compilation fails**.

### 2.3.2 `super.fieldName` — Resolving Shadowing

**Why use it?** If the child class declares a field with the **same name** as the parent's field, the child's version **shadows** the parent's. `super.fieldName` disambiguates.

### 2.3.3 `super.methodName()` — Calling Overridden Parent Method

**Why use it?** Inside an overriding method, you can **extend** the parent's behavior rather than fully replacing it. This is the canonical pattern for **open-closed principle** extension.

---

## 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

> [!NOTE]
> The following table summarizes **all** high-yield concepts from this topic. Memorize this — it covers ~80% of what KTU examiners test.

| # | Concept | Syntax Rule | KTU Exam Memory Hook |
|---|---------|-------------|----------------------|
| 1 | Member Inner Class instantiation | `OuterObj.new Inner()` | Outer instance **mandatory** |
| 2 | Static Nested Class instantiation | `new Outer.Nested()` | No outer instance needed |
| 3 | Local Inner Class scope | Declared inside `{ }` block | Dies at block exit |
| 4 | Effectively final variable | Assigned once, never reassigned | Accessible from local/anonymous class |
| 5 | Anonymous Inner Class | `new Interface() { ... };` | **One-shot**, no name |
| 6 | Inheritance declaration | `class Child extends Parent` | Single inheritance only |
| 7 | IS-A relationship | `Child IS-A Parent` | Compiler-enforced substitutability |
| 8 | `super()` position | **First statement** of constructor | Otherwise compile error |
| 9 | Auto `super()` insertion | When no `this()` / `super()` written | Calls no-arg parent constructor |
| 10 | Overriding signature match | `name + parameters` identical | Return type same or covariant |
| 11 | `@Override` annotation | Optional but **best practice** | Catches signature mismatch at compile time |
| 12 | Access modifier widening | Child can widen, not narrow | `private → public` ✅, `public → private` ❌ |
| 13 | `super.field` shadowing resolution | Disambiguates same-named fields | Child shadow hides parent version |
| 14 | `super.method()` extension | Calls parent's overridden version | Used inside overriding method |
| 15 | Final class / method | Cannot be extended / overridden | `final class X {}` / `final void m(){}` |

