# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete Worked Example — Inner Class Hierarchy

Below is an **exhaustive**, compileable Java program that demonstrates **all four inner class types** in a single coherent scenario. Each line is annotated.

```java
// File: CollegeSystem.java
class College {                       // OUTER CLASS

    private String name = "KTU";      // Outer instance field
    private static String code = "APJKTU";  // Outer static field

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // (A) MEMBER INNER CLASS — non-static, tied to College instance
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    class Department {                // Member Inner Class
        String deptName = "CSE";

        void display() {
            // Can access BOTH static and non-static outer members
            System.out.println("College: " + name);           // ✅ non-static OK
            System.out.println("Code: " + code);              // ✅ static OK
            System.out.println("Outer ref: " + College.this.name); // ✅ explicit
            System.out.println("Dept: " + deptName);
        }
    }

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // (B) STATIC NESTED CLASS — no outer instance needed
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    static class ExamCell {           // Static Nested Class
        void conductExam() {
            // Can ONLY access static outer members directly
            System.out.println("Conducting exam for: " + code);   // ✅ static OK

            // System.out.println(name);   // ❌ COMPILE ERROR: non-static
            // To access non-static, must create outer instance:
            College c = new College();
            System.out.println("Via object: " + c.name);          // ✅ via obj
        }
    }

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // (C) METHOD with LOCAL INNER CLASS inside it
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    public void registerStudent(final int rollNo) {  // 'final' or effectively final
        final String branch = "Computer Science";     // required for capture

        // LOCAL INNER CLASS — declared inside this method
        class StudentRecord {
            void print() {
                // Can access outer + effectively final locals
                System.out.println("Roll: " + rollNo);   // ✅ captured
                System.out.println("Branch: " + branch); // ✅ captured
                System.out.println("College: " + name);  // ✅ outer
            }
        }

        StudentRecord sr = new StudentRecord();  // instantiated here only
        sr.print();
        // sr is destroyed when method exits
    }

    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    // (D) METHOD returning ANONYMOUS INNER CLASS instance
    // ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    public Runnable getAuditor() {
        final String auditorName = "Audit Dept";

        // Anonymous Inner Class implementing Runnable interface
        return new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println("Audit by: " + auditorName); // ✅ captured
                System.out.println("For: " + name);              // ✅ outer
            }
        };
    }
}

// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// DRIVER CLASS — shows how each inner class is instantiated
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
public class CollegeSystem {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // (A) Member Inner Class — needs outer object FIRST
        College c1 = new College();
        College.Department d = c1.new Department();   // ← KEY SYNTAX
        d.display();

        // (B) Static Nested Class — directly via outer class name
        College.ExamCell ec = new College.ExamCell();  // ← NO outer obj needed
        ec.conductExam();

        // (C) Local Inner Class — used inside registerStudent()
        c1.registerStudent(101);

        // (D) Anonymous Inner Class — returned as Runnable
        Runnable r = c1.getAuditor();
        r.run();
    }
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
College: KTU
Code: APJKTU
Outer ref: KTU
Dept: CSE
Conducting exam for: APJKTU
Via object: KTU
Roll: 101
Branch: Computer Science
College: KTU
Audit by: Audit Dept
For: KTU
```

**Step-by-Step Logical Deduction:**

1. **Step 1 — Member Inner Class `Department`:** Created with `c1.new Department()`. Has implicit reference `College.this` pointing to `c1`. Can access `name` (private outer field) directly.
2. **Step 2 — Static Nested Class `ExamCell`:** Created with `new College.ExamCell()` — no outer object needed. Can only touch `code` directly; needs `c` reference to touch `name`.
3. **Step 3 — Local Inner Class `StudentRecord`:** Lives *only* inside `registerStudent()`. Captures `rollNo` and `branch` because they are `final`. Dies when method returns.
4. **Step 4 — Anonymous Inner Class `Runnable`:** Instantiated inline. No name, no constructor. Captures `auditorName`. Polymorphic — `Runnable r` holds the reference.

