### **Model Solution for Question B**

#### **Part (a) — Inheritance Types**

**Definition:** Inheritance is the mechanism by which one class acquires properties and methods of another class, enabling **code reuse** and **polymorphism**.

**1. Single Inheritance** — One parent, one child:

```java
class Animal {
    void eat() { System.out.println("Eating..."); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() { System.out.println("Barking..."); }
}
// Usage: Dog d = new Dog(); d.eat(); d.bark();
```

**2. Multilevel Inheritance** — Chain of inheritance:

```java
class Animal { void eat() { System.out.println("Eating"); } }
class Mammal extends Animal { void walk() { System.out.println("Walking"); } }
class Dog extends Mammal { void bark() { System.out.println("Barking"); } }
// Dog inherits from BOTH Mammal AND Animal (transitively)
```

**3. Hierarchical Inheritance** — One parent, multiple children:

```java
class Shape {
    void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing shape"); }
}
class Circle extends Shape {
    @Override void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing circle"); }
}
class Square extends Shape {
    @Override void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing square"); }
}
// Circle and Square both inherit from Shape independently
```

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout:**
> - **Java does NOT support multiple inheritance with classes.** If asked *"Does Java support multiple inheritance?"*, answer: *"No, Java supports multiple inheritance only through interfaces, not classes, to avoid the Diamond Problem."*
> - **Confusion alert:** Students often confuse "Hierarchical" with "Hybrid". Hybrid is a combination of two or more types and is achieved only via interfaces in Java.

#### **Part (b) — All Four Inner Classes in One Application**

```java
// OUTER CLASS
class Library {
    private String libName = "KTU Central Library";
    private static String city = "Thiruvananthapuram";

    // (1) MEMBER INNER CLASS
    class Book {
        String title;
        Book(String t) { this.title = t; }
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Book: " + title + " in " + libName);
        }
    }

    // (2) STATIC NESTED CLASS
    static class Librarian {
        void greet() {
            System.out.println("Librarian of " + city + " welcomes you");
        }
    }

    // Method with (3) LOCAL and (4) ANONYMOUS inner classes
    public void issueBook(final String member) {

        // (3) LOCAL INNER CLASS
        class IssueSlip {
            void print() {
                System.out.println("Issued to: " + member);
            }
        }
        new IssueSlip().print();

        // (4) ANONYMOUS INNER CLASS (Runnable)
        Runnable r = new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                System.out.println("Notification sent to: " + member);
            }
        };
        r.run();
    }
}

// DRIVER
public class LibraryApp {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Library lib = new Library();

        // (1) Member Inner — needs outer obj
        Library.Book b = lib.new Book("OOP in Java");
        b.show();

        // (2) Static Nested — direct instantiation
        Library.Librarian l = new Library.Librarian();
        l.greet();

        // (3) Local + (4) Anonymous — used inside method
        lib.issueBook("Rahul");
    }
}
```

**Output:**
```
Book: OOP in Java in KTU Central Library
Librarian of Thiruvananthapuram welcomes you
Issued to: Rahul
Notification sent to: Rahul
```

**Instantiation Summary Table (Marks-bearing):**

| Type | Syntax Used in `main` |
|------|----------------------|
| Member Inner | `lib.new Book("OOP in Java")` |
| Static Nested | `new Library.Librarian()` |
| Local Inner | `new IssueSlip()` *(inside method only)* |
| Anonymous | `new Runnable() { ... }` *(inline)* |

