# Section 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

In Object-Oriented Programming (OOP), **Inheritance** is a mechanism by which a new class (called the **subclass**, **derived class**, or **child class**) is created from an existing class (called the **superclass**, **base class**, or **parent class**). The subclass inherits (acquires) the attributes (fields) and behaviors (methods) of the superclass, and may additionally define its own unique members or override inherited behaviors.

**Types of Inheritance** refers to the various structural relationships and hierarchies that can be formed between classes through inheritance. According to the KTU 2024 Scheme syllabus for PECIT633, the **five principal types** of inheritance recognized in OOP theory are:

1. **Single Inheritance** – One subclass inherits from one superclass.
2. **Multiple Inheritance** – One subclass inherits from two or more superclasses.
3. **Multilevel Inheritance** – A chain of inheritance: subclass → intermediate class → superclass.
4. **Hierarchical Inheritance** – One superclass serves as the parent for multiple subclasses.
5. **Hybrid Inheritance** – A combination of two or more of the above types, typically resulting in a **Diamond Problem**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Focus Point:** In Java (the reference language for PECIT633), classes support **Single, Multilevel, and Hierarchical** inheritance directly. **Multiple and Hybrid** inheritance between *classes* is **not supported** in Java to avoid the *Diamond/Ambiguity Problem*. Java achieves multiple inheritance through **interfaces**.

## 1.2 Intuitive Overview – Real-World Analogy

Imagine a **family tree** or a **biological taxonomy**:
- A **Parent** passes traits (eye color, surname, mannerisms) to their **Child**.
- The **Child** is the *subclass*, the **Parent** is the *superclass*.
- The **Child** does not merely copy the Parent — it **extends** the family by adding its own skills (e.g., a Doctor child of a Teacher parent inherits teaching traits but adds medical expertise).

Now, extend this analogy:
- **Single** = One child, one parent (you and your mother).
- **Multilevel** = Grandparent → Parent → Child (your lineage across generations).
- **Hierarchical** = One parent, multiple children (your mother is parent to you and your sibling).
- **Multiple** = A child having *two* biological parents (Java forbids this for classes to avoid legal/biological confusion!).
- **Hybrid** = A blended family tree combining several patterns.

## 1.3 Why Inheritance Matters in OOP

- **Code Reusability:** Write once in the parent, reuse in children.
- **Method Overriding (Runtime Polymorphism):** Subclasses customize inherited behavior.
- **Establishes IS-A Relationship:** A `Car` *is-a* `Vehicle`.
- **Supports Extensibility:** Add new features without modifying existing tested code (Open/Closed Principle).

> [!NOTE]
> **Standard OOP Metric:** The depth of inheritance (longest chain from root to leaf) is called the **Inheritance Depth (D)**. Best practices in industry (e.g., Oracle Java Guidelines) recommend keeping **D ≤ 3 to 4** to avoid fragile base-class problems.

