# Section 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Detailed Breakdown of Each Inheritance Type

### 2.1.1 Single Inheritance
- **Definition:** A subclass inherits from exactly one direct superclass.
- **Structure:** A → B (one parent, one child).
- **Java Syntax:** `class B extends A { }`
- **Use Case:** Most common form; establishes a clear linear hierarchy.

### 2.1.2 Multiple Inheritance (Class Level)
- **Definition:** A subclass inherits from **two or more** superclasses simultaneously.
- **Structure:** A → C, B → C (two parents, one child).
- **Java Status:** ❌ **Not supported** for classes.
- **C++ Status:** ✅ Supported (with ambiguity risks).
- **Java Alternative:** Achieved via interfaces: `class C implements A, B { }`

### 2.1.3 Multilevel Inheritance
- **Definition:** A chain of inheritance, like a ladder: Grandparent → Parent → Child.
- **Structure:** A → B → C → D ...
- **Property:** Transitive — features propagate down the chain.
- **Java Support:** ✅ Fully supported.

### 2.1.4 Hierarchical Inheritance
- **Definition:** One superclass is inherited by **multiple** subclasses.
- **Structure:** A → B, A → C, A → D (tree-branch pattern).
- **Java Support:** ✅ Fully supported. All subclasses share the `extends` keyword with the same parent.

### 2.1.5 Hybrid Inheritance
- **Definition:** A combination of two or more inheritance types — e.g., Hierarchical + Multiple, forming a **diamond shape**.
- **Structure:** Class D inherits from B and C, both of which inherit from A.
- **The Diamond Problem:** Ambiguity arises when class D inherits the same method from both B and C, leading to compile-time conflict.
- **Java Solution:** Interfaces resolve this because interfaces can hold only `abstract` (or `default` since Java 8) methods, and the implementing class must explicitly resolve ambiguity.

### 2.1.6 Multipath Inheritance (Conceptual Variant)
- A subclass inherits from two classes that themselves share a common ancestor (essentially the diamond without full hybrid complexity).

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Inheritance Type | Class Diagram Shape | Java Class Support | Java Interface Support | Ambiguity Risk | Time Complexity (Method Lookup) |
|:---|:---|:---|:---|:---|:---|
| **Single** | Linear (A → B) | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | None | O(1) direct |
| **Multilevel** | Ladder (A → B → C) | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (via `extends`) | None | O(D) where D = depth |
| **Hierarchical** | Tree (A → B, C, D) | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | None | O(1) to parent |
| **Multiple (Classes)** | Diamond branches | ❌ **No** | ✅ Yes (via `implements`) | **High** | N/A (not allowed) |
| **Hybrid** | Diamond shape | ❌ **No** | ✅ Yes | **Highest** | N/A (resolved via interfaces) |
| **Multipath** | Diamond subset | ❌ **No** | ✅ Yes | **High** | N/A (resolved via interfaces) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Diamond Problem (KTU High-Yield):** When two paths in a multiple/hybrid inheritance convey the same method to a subclass, and both super-classes derive it from a common ancestor, **the compiler cannot decide which version to inherit**. This is the **Ambiguity Error**.

## 2.3 Engineering Utility

- **GUI Frameworks (JavaFX, Swing):** Hierarchical inheritance — `JButton extends JButton extends AbstractButton extends JComponent extends Container extends Component extends Object`.
- **JDBC API:** Multilevel interfaces — `Statement extends Wrapper extends AutoCloseable`.
- **Design Patterns:** *Template Method Pattern* uses inheritance to let subclasses redefine steps of an algorithm without changing structure.
- **E-commerce Systems:** Product hierarchy — `Electronics`, `Clothing`, `Books` all inherit from `Product`.

