# Section 3: Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Analytical Reasoning: Why Java Forbids Multiple Inheritance for Classes

We can mathematically model inheritance as a directed acyclic graph (DAG) where each node represents a class and each edge represents an `extends` or `implements` relationship.

For Java classes, the constraint is:

$$
\forall \text{ class } C: \quad \vert \text{super}(C)\vert = 1
$$

That is, every class has **exactly one direct superclass** (excluding `Object`, which is implicit). This is a strict DAG constraint — the in-degree of every node (except `Object`) must be **exactly 1**.

For Java interfaces, the constraint relaxes to:

$$
\forall \text{ interface } I: \quad \vert \text{super}(I)\vert \geq 0
$$

And for classes implementing interfaces:

$$
\forall \text{ class } C: \quad \vert \text{implemented interfaces}(C)\vert \geq 0
$$

This structural difference eliminates the Diamond Problem at the class level.

## 3.2 Diamond Problem Resolution – Step-by-Step Analysis

Consider the diamond structure:

$$
A \;\; \rightarrow \;\; B, \quad A \;\; \rightarrow \;\; C, \quad B \;\; \rightarrow \;\; D, \quad C \;\; \rightarrow \;\; D
$$

If class `A` defines `methodM()`, and both `B` and `C` inherit (without overriding) `methodM()`, then `D` has **two paths** to reach `methodM()`:

$$
D.methodM() \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; B.methodM() \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; A.methodM()
$$

$$
D.methodM() \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; C.methodM() \;\;\Rightarrow\;\; A.methodM()
$$

**Step-by-step Java resolution using interfaces:**

```java
interface A {
    default void methodM() {
        System.out.println("A.methodM()");
    }
}
interface B extends A {
    @Override
    default void methodM() {
        System.out.println("B.methodM()");
    }
}
interface C extends A {
    @Override
    default void methodM() {
        System.out.println("C.methodM()");
    }
}
class D implements B, C {
    @Override
    public void methodM() {
        C.super.methodM(); // Explicit disambiguation
    }
}
```

**Resolution Logic:**
1. If `D` provides its own `methodM()` → uses `D`'s version.
2. If `D` is silent but `B` and `C` disagree → **compile-time error** unless `D` uses `Interface.super.method()` syntax.
3. If `B` and `C` agree (same signature) → no conflict.
4. If neither `B` nor `C` declares `methodM()`, but both inherit from `A` → no conflict.

## 3.3 Analytical Matrix: Inheritance Depth vs. Maintainability

$$
\text{Maintainability Index (MI)} \;\;\propto\;\; \frac{1}{1 + \alpha \cdot D}
$$

Where:

$$
D = \text{Inheritance Depth}, \quad \alpha = 0.15 \text{ (empirical weight constant)}
$$

This shows that as depth `D` increases, maintainability degrades non-linearly, justifying the industry recommendation of **D ≤ 4**.

## 3.4 Inheritance Member Accessibility Rules (Java)

$$
\text{Visibility Hierarchy:} \quad \text{private} \;<\; \text{default} \;<\; \text{protected} \;<\; \text{public}
$$

| Modifier | Same Class | Same Package | Subclass (Different Package) | Other Classes |
|:---|:---:|:---:|:---:|:---:|
| `private` | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `default` | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `protected` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ❌ |
| `public` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

