## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Common Mark-Deduction Pitfalls (as per KTU Valuation Key Patterns):**
> 
> 1. **Forgetting the `extends` keyword syntax:** Students often write `class B A` instead of `class B extends A`. **−1 mark** per instance.
> 
> 2. **Confusing `extends` with `implements`:** A class `extends` another class, but `implements` an interface. Mixing these is a **−2 mark** penalty.
> 
> 3. **Not invoking `super()` in subclass constructors:** When a parameterized parent constructor exists, failing to call `super(args)` causes a compile error. Examiners often award partial credit but deduct **−1 mark** for absence.
> 
> 4. **Claiming Java "supports multiple inheritance":** Saying Java supports multiple inheritance at the class level is **incorrect** — marks are lost immediately. Always clarify: *Java does not support multiple inheritance for classes; it supports it via interfaces.*
> 
> 5. **Missing diagrams in theory answers:** For 7-mark questions on inheritance types, diagrams carry **2–3 marks** by themselves. Always include a class/structural diagram.
> 
> 6. **Not explaining the Diamond Problem:** When asked "why" Java restricts multiple inheritance, merely stating "ambiguity" without elaborating loses marks. Always describe the diamond structure and resolution mechanism.

