## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ **Inheritance** enables code reuse and establishes IS-A relationships between classes.
- ✅ **Java supports** Single, Multilevel, and Hierarchical inheritance directly through classes.
- ✅ **Java does NOT support** Multiple or Hybrid inheritance through classes — only through interfaces.
- ✅ **Diamond Problem** occurs when a class inherits the same method through multiple paths from a common ancestor.
- ✅ **Java 8+** introduces `default` methods in interfaces, which can be overridden in implementing classes to resolve ambiguity.
- ✅ The `super` keyword refers to the immediate parent class; `super()` calls the parent constructor.
- ✅ **Method overriding** is allowed only when the parent method is not `static`, `final`, or `private`.
- ✅ **Constructors** are NOT inherited, but the parent's constructor is implicitly called via `super()`.
- ✅ **Object class** is the ultimate superclass of all Java classes (root of inheritance hierarchy).
- ✅ Use **protected** access modifier for members that subclasses (in different packages) need to access.
- ✅ Industry best practice: Keep **inheritance depth ≤ 4** to maintain code maintainability.
- ✅ Always remember the **Diamond Problem** as the primary reason Java forbids multiple class inheritance.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Final KTU Tip:** When answering inheritance questions, **always draw the class diagram first**, then write the code. Examiners reward visual clarity. For 14-mark questions, dedicate ~3 marks worth of content to diagrams and ~4 marks each to code + explanation.

