## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Exhaustive C++ Example: The Inheritance Access Ladder

Let us derive the behavior of `protected` members step-by-step using a C++ program.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// ===== Step 1: Define a base class =====
class Shape {
private:
    int secretID = 999;          // PRIVATE: only Shape can see this

protected:
    int width;                   // PROTECTED: Shape and its children can see
    int height;

public:
    void setDimensions(int w, int h) {
        width = w;               // Shape can access its own protected member
        height = h;
    }
    void display() {
        cout << "Width = " << width << ", Height = " << height << endl;
    }
};

// ===== Step 2: Define a derived class =====
class Rectangle : public Shape {
public:
    int calculateArea() {
        // width and height are PROTECTED in Shape.
        // They are inherited as PROTECTED (because of public inheritance).
        // So a derived class CAN access them directly.
        return width * height;
    }
};

int main() {
    Rectangle r;
    r.setDimensions(10, 5);
    r.display();
    cout << "Area = " << r.calculateArea() << endl;

    // r.width = 20;     // ❌ ERROR! 'width' is protected; not accessible from main()
    // r.secretID = 1;   // ❌ ERROR! 'secretID' is private
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-step logical trace of the program:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Line: } r.setDimensions(10, 5) &\Rightarrow \text{public call allowed} \rightarrow \text{width}=10, \text{height}=5 \\
\text{Line: } r.display() &\Rightarrow \text{public call allowed} \rightarrow \text{prints dimensions} \\
\text{Line: } r.calculateArea() &\Rightarrow \text{public call invokes protected data internally} \\
\text{Line: } r.width = 20 &\Rightarrow \text{COMPILE ERROR: 'width' is protected, main() is not a derived class} \\
\text{Line: } r.secretID = 1 &\Rightarrow \text{COMPILE ERROR: 'secretID' is private, inaccessible everywhere outside Shape}
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.2 Java Equivalent (For Comparison)

In Java, `protected` is **package-level + inheritance-level** access. Let us derive the same logic:

```java
package shapes;

public class Shape {
    private int secretID = 999;
    protected int width;
    protected int height;

    public void setDimensions(int w, int h) {
        this.width = w;
        this.height = h;
    }
}
```

```java
package shapes;  // SAME package

public class Rectangle extends Shape {
    public int calculateArea() {
        return this.width * this.height;  // ✅ OK because same package OR derived class
    }
}
```

### 3.3 Analytical Access Matrix (The Master Reference Table)

We now consolidate the behavior into a complete access matrix that KTU examiners love to test.

| Member declared in `Base` as | Accessed from `Base` (itself) | Accessed from `Derived` (subclass) | Accessed from `main()` (outside, unrelated) |
|---|---|---|---|
| `private` | ✅ Yes | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| `protected` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| `public` | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes (subject to inheritance mode) | ✅ Yes |

> [!NOTE]
> **Important KTU Trap:**
> In C++, the visibility of inherited `protected` members inside a derived class can be further changed using the access mode of inheritance:
> - `public` inheritance → protected stays protected.
> - `protected` inheritance → protected stays protected.
> - `private` inheritance → protected becomes private to the derived class.

