## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
*Define the `protected` access specifier in C++. How does it differ from `private` and `public`?*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
The `protected` access specifier in C++ makes class members accessible in two scopes: (i) within the class in which they are declared, and (ii) within all classes derived from that class. Members declared as `private` are accessible only within the class itself and not by derived classes. Members declared as `public` are accessible everywhere — within the class, derived classes, and from any external code. Thus, `protected` provides a controlled middle ground: it supports inheritance while preserving encapsulation from the outside world.

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**
*Can a `protected` member of a base class be accessed directly from `main()` in C++? Justify your answer.*

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
**No**, a `protected` member of a base class cannot be accessed directly from `main()` or any non-derived function/class. The `protected` access specifier restricts visibility to the defining class and its derived classes only. Since `main()` is neither a member of the base class nor a derived class, it is treated as outside code and is denied access. Attempting to access a `protected` member from `main()` results in a **compile-time error**.

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each — Module Internal Choice)

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)** — *[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]*

**(a)** Explain the three access specifiers in C++ with suitable examples. Mention the role of `protected` in inheritance. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a C++ program to demonstrate that a `protected` data member of a base class is accessible inside a derived class but not in `main()`. Show the relevant compile-time errors as comments. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution for Question A

**Part (a) — 7 marks:**

The three access specifiers in C++ are:

1. **`private`**: Members are accessible only within the class that declares them. They are not accessible to derived classes or to the outside world. This is the **default** access for class members in C++ (and for classes declared with the `class` keyword).

2. **`protected`**: Members are accessible within the declaring class and within all its derived classes (and their further descendants). They are **not** accessible from outside code such as `main()` or unrelated classes. This specifier exists specifically to support inheritance without breaking encapsulation.

3. **`public`**: Members are accessible from anywhere — within the class, derived classes, and any external code.

**Role of `protected` in inheritance:**
`protected` allows a base class to share selected implementation details (such as helper functions, internal counters, or shared dimensions) with its derived classes, while still hiding them from unrelated code. This enables derived classes to extend or override behavior efficiently without exposing internal data to the public API. For example, a base `Shape` class can declare `protected int width, height` so that derived `Rectangle` and `Triangle` classes can directly compute area using these fields, but the outside world must go through public setter functions.

**Part (b) — 7 marks:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Base {
private:
    int pvt = 1;       // private: only Base can access
protected:
    int prot = 2;      // protected: Base and Derived can access
public:
    int pub = 3;       // public: everyone can access
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void show() {
        // cout << pvt;  // ERROR: 'pvt' is private in Base
        cout << "Protected = " << prot << endl;  // OK: Derived can access
        cout << "Public = "    << pub  << endl;  // OK: Public is accessible everywhere
    }
};

int main() {
    Derived d;
    d.show();

    cout << "Public = " << d.pub << endl;     // OK: public member
    // cout << d.prot;                         // ERROR: 'prot' is protected
    // cout << d.pvt;                          // ERROR: 'pvt' is private
    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
Protected = 2
Public = 3
Public = 3
```

The two commented lines in `main()` would produce **compile-time errors** because `prot` and `pvt` are not accessible outside the class hierarchy. The line `cout << "Protected = " << prot` inside `Derived::show()` works because derived classes are granted access to `protected` members of the base.

---

### **Question B (14 Marks)** — *[KTU University Exam – June 2024]*

**(a)** Compare and contrast `protected` access in **C++** and **Java**. Which one offers broader visibility and why? **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Design a class hierarchy: `Employee` (base) → `Manager` (derived) → `SeniorManager` (further derived). Demonstrate multi-level inheritance with `protected` salary data, accessed across all three levels. Provide the complete C++ code with output. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution for Question B

**Part (a) — 7 marks:**

| Feature | C++ `protected` | Java `protected` |
|---|---|---|
| Accessible in same class | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Accessible in derived class | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Accessible in same package | ❌ No (must derive) | ✅ Yes |
| Accessible from outside via object | ❌ No | ❌ No |
| Default access for class members | `private` | Package-private (default) |

**C++ `protected`**: Strictly limited to the defining class and any derived class. Other classes in the same project file (translation unit) cannot access it unless they are derived.

**Java `protected`**: Broader — accessible within the **same package** OR within a subclass (even if the subclass is in a different package). This is sometimes called the **"package + inheritance"** model.

**Conclusion**: Java's `protected` is broader because it includes package-level access, which C++ does not. C++ relies on `friend` declarations for similar functionality.

**Part (b) — 7 marks:**

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// Level 1: Base class
class Employee {
protected:
    double basicSalary;
public:
    void setBasic(double s) { basicSalary = s; }
};

// Level 2: Derived from Employee
class Manager : public Employee {
protected:
    double bonus;
public:
    void setBonus(double b) { bonus = b; }
    double getManagerTotal() {
        return basicSalary + bonus;   // accesses base's protected member
    }
};

// Level 3: Further derived from Manager
class SeniorManager : public Manager {
private:
    double stockOptions;
public:
    void setStock(double s) { stockOptions = s; }
    double getSeniorTotal() {
        return basicSalary + bonus + stockOptions;  // accesses both ancestors' protected data
    }
};

int main() {
    SeniorManager sm;
    sm.setBasic(50000);
    sm.setBonus(20000);
    sm.setStock(15000);

    cout << "Manager-level total  = " << sm.getManagerTotal()  << endl;
    cout << "Senior-level total   = " << sm.getSeniorTotal()  << endl;

    // cout << sm.basicSalary;   // ERROR: protected, inaccessible from main
    // cout << sm.bonus;         // ERROR: protected, inaccessible from main
    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**
```
Manager-level total  = 70000
Senior-level total   = 85000
```

This program demonstrates that `protected` members flow down through multi-level inheritance chains. `SeniorManager` can directly use `basicSalary` (declared in `Employee`) and `bonus` (declared in `Manager`) because both are `protected`. However, `main()` is still blocked from accessing them directly.

