### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- ✅ `protected` is one of the three access specifiers in C++ (`private`, `protected`, `public`).
- ✅ It is **accessible within the defining class** and **all its derived classes** (including multi-level descendants).
- ✅ It is **NOT accessible** from `main()` or any unrelated class.
- ✅ It exists **specifically to support inheritance** while preserving encapsulation.
- ✅ In C++, `protected` works only through inheritance — it does **not** grant package-level access like Java does.
- ✅ In Java, `protected` = **package + subclass** access (broader than C++).
- ✅ Private members **are inherited** in C++ but are **inaccessible** to derived classes.
- ✅ The **default access** for class members in C++ is `private`; for `struct` it is `public`.
- ✅ When a `protected` member is inherited via `private` inheritance, it becomes `private` in the derived class (and is then no longer accessible to further derived classes).
- ✅ Friend functions/classes (C++) can access `protected` and `private` members, but this is a separate mechanism.
- ✅ `protected` is heavily used in **framework design, GUI libraries, game engines, and device drivers** where base classes must share internals with specialized derived classes.
- ✅ KTU frequently tests: definitions, access matrix questions, code-output prediction, and C++ vs Java comparisons on this topic.

