## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> **Dynamic Method Dispatch (DMD)** is the mechanism by which a call to an **overridden method** is resolved at **runtime (during program execution)** rather than at **compile time**, based on the **actual type of the object** being referred to (and not the type of the reference variable). In Java, DMD is the underlying mechanism that enables **Runtime Polymorphism**.

In KTU 2024 Scheme terminology, this concept is also referred to as **Late Binding** or **Runtime Binding**. The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) — not the compiler — is the entity responsible for determining which method implementation to invoke.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy

> [!NOTE]  
> **Real-world Analogy — The Universal Remote Control**  
> Imagine a universal TV remote (the **parent class reference**) that can point to a Sony TV, an LG TV, or a Samsung TV (the **child class objects**). The remote has a single button labeled "Power". When you press the button, the *actual TV currently connected* responds — not the remote's internal memory of "some generic TV".  
> - The **reference** = the remote (type is known at compile time).  
> - The **object** = the actual TV plugged in (type is known only at runtime).  
> - The **action** = calling `powerButton()`. The *real* TV's power method executes.  

This is precisely what Dynamic Method Dispatch does — the *reference variable* decides *what message can be sent*, but the *actual object* decides *how that message is executed*.

### 1.3 Pre-requisites for Dynamic Method Dispatch

For DMD to function correctly in Java, **three mandatory conditions** must be satisfied:

1. **Inheritance** must exist (a parent–child class relationship).
2. **Method Overriding** must occur (child class redefines a parent class method with the exact same signature).
3. **Upcasting** must be performed (parent reference = child object).

### 1.4 Why DMD is Critical in OOP

- It is the **technical backbone** of **Runtime Polymorphism**.
- It allows **decoupling** of code (programs depend on abstract types, not concrete implementations).
- It is foundational to **Design Patterns** like Strategy, Template Method, and Factory.
- It enables **extensibility** — new subclasses can be added without modifying existing client code (Open/Closed Principle).

