## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Reference Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Mechanics — How DMD Works Internally

The process of Dynamic Method Dispatch follows this precise sequence at runtime:

- **Step 1 — Compilation Phase:** The Java compiler verifies that the method being called exists in the **reference type's class hierarchy** (parent class). It does *not* decide which version to call. If the method is not found in the parent, a compile-time error occurs.
- **Step 2 — Object Creation:** At runtime, an object of the child class is created on the heap. Its **vtable (virtual method table)** contains the address of the *child's overridden* method.
- **Step 3 — Reference Assignment (Upcasting):** A parent class reference is assigned the child object: `Parent p = new Child();`
- **Step 4 — Method Invocation:** When `p.overriddenMethod()` is called, the JVM consults the object's vtable (not the reference type) to find the actual method address.
- **Step 5 — Dynamic Binding:** The child's version of the method is bound and executed.

### 2.2 Critical Rules & Limitations

> [!WARNING]  
> **Rules That Students Frequently Forget in KTU Exams:**

- **Only overridden (instance) methods** are dispatched dynamically.  
- **Static methods** are bound at compile time (they undergo **Method Hiding**, not overriding, and follow **Static Binding**).  
- **Private methods** cannot be overridden, hence cannot be dynamically dispatched.  
- **Final methods** cannot be overridden → no dynamic dispatch.  
- **Fields (instance variables)** are **not** polymorphically dispatched — they are always resolved based on the **reference type**.  
- **Constructors** are not polymorphic.  
- DMD works **only through inheritance** (IS-A relationship). Interfaces (from Java 8 with default methods) also participate in DMD.

### 2.3 KTU High-Yield Reference Table

| Concept | Compile-Time Behaviour | Runtime Behaviour | Dispatch Type |
|---|---|---|---|
| Overridden Instance Method | Method existence checked in parent class | JVM binds to **child's** version | **Dynamic (Late)** |
| Static Method | Bound to reference type class | Already resolved | **Static (Early)** |
| Private Method | Resolved at compile time | Already resolved | **Static (Early)** |
| Final Method | Resolved at compile time | Already resolved | **Static (Early)** |
| Instance Variable | Resolved at compile time | Always **reference type's** variable | **Not applicable** |
| Constructor | Resolved at compile time | Chain of calls resolved | **Static chain** |

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Framework Design:** Spring, Hibernate, and Java EE heavily use DMD to inject behavior at runtime.  
- **Plugin Architectures:** IDEs like Eclipse and IntelliJ use DMD to load extensions dynamically.  
- **GUI Event Handling:** AWT/Swing listeners use DMD to bind generic event handlers to specific components.  
- **Game Development:** Calling `draw()` on a generic `GameObject` reference renders different shapes (Circle, Square, Triangle) polymorphically.  
- **Dependency Injection:** The Hollywood Principle — *"Don't call us, we'll call you"* — is a direct application of DMD.

