## 3. Step-by-Step Code Analysis & Trace Tables

### 3.1 Foundational Java Example — Demonstrating DMD

```java
// Parent class
class Vehicle {
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle is running");
    }
}

// Child class
class Car extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Car is running safely at 100 km/h");
    }
}

// Another Child class
class Bike extends Vehicle {
    @Override
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Bike is running safely at 60 km/h");
    }
}

// Driver class
public class DynamicDispatchDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Vehicle v;          // Reference of type Vehicle (parent)

        v = new Car();      // Upcasting: Vehicle ref -> Car object
        v.run();            // Output: "Car is running safely at 100 km/h"

        v = new Bike();     // Upcasting: Vehicle ref -> Bike object
        v.run();            // Output: "Bike is running safely at 60 km/h"

        v = new Vehicle();  // Normal instantiation
        v.run();            // Output: "Vehicle is running"
    }
}
```

### 3.2 Exhaustive Trace Table — Step-by-Step Execution

| Step | Statement | Reference `v` Holds | Object Type on Heap | Method Invoked | Output |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `Vehicle v;` | `null` | — | — | — |
| 2 | `v = new Car();` | `Vehicle` (compile-time) | `Car` | — | — |
| 3 | `v.run();` | `Vehicle` | `Car` | `Car.run()` (dynamic) | "Car is running safely at 100 km/h" |
| 4 | `v = new Bike();` | `Vehicle` (compile-time) | `Bike` | — | — |
| 5 | `v.run();` | `Vehicle` | `Bike` | `Bike.run()` (dynamic) | "Bike is running safely at 60 km/h" |
| 6 | `v = new Vehicle();` | `Vehicle` | `Vehicle` | — | — |
| 7 | `v.run();` | `Vehicle` | `Vehicle` | `Vehicle.run()` | "Vehicle is running" |

### 3.3 Common Pitfall Example — Variable vs Method Resolution

```java
class Parent {
    String name = "Parent";
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Parent method, name = " + name);
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    String name = "Child";  // Hides, not overrides
    @Override
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Child method, name = " + name);
    }
}

public class VariableBindingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Parent p = new Child();
        System.out.println(p.name);  // Compile-time: "Parent"
        p.display();                  // Runtime: "Child method, name = Child"
    }
}
```

> [!NOTE]  
> **Output Trace:**  
> - `p.name` → prints **"Parent"** (fields are bound at compile time to the reference type).  
> - `p.display()` → prints **"Child method, name = Child"** (methods are bound at runtime to the object type — DMD in action).  

### 3.4 Static Method Behaviour — Method Hiding vs Overriding

```java
class Super {
    static void show() {
        System.out.println("Super static show()");
    }
    void instanceShow() {
        System.out.println("Super instance show()");
    }
}

class Sub extends Super {
    static void show() {  // Method Hiding, not overriding
        System.out.println("Sub static show()");
    }
    @Override
    void instanceShow() {
        System.out.println("Sub instance show()");
    }
}

public class StaticBindingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Super s = new Sub();
        s.show();          // Compile-time: "Super static show()"
        s.instanceShow();  // Runtime:      "Sub instance show()"
    }
}
```

### 3.5 Mathematical Analogy (Conceptual)

Although DMD is not a numerical concept, the dispatch decision can be expressed as a runtime function:

$$M_{called} = f(R, O, VTable)$$

where:
- $R$ = Reference variable type (compile-time check)
- $O$ = Actual object on heap (runtime check)
- $VTable$ = Method table associated with object's class

The function $f$ is evaluated **at runtime** for instance methods, and **at compile time** for static, private, and final methods.

