#### **Question A (14 Marks)** — **[KTU University Exam - Dec 2024, Series II]**

**(a)** Explain the concept of **Dynamic Method Dispatch** in Java with a suitable example. List the conditions required for Dynamic Method Dispatch to work. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**Definition (2 marks):**  
Dynamic Method Dispatch is the runtime mechanism in Java wherein a call to an overridden method is resolved based on the **actual object type** (not the reference type) by the JVM. It is the implementation of **runtime polymorphism**.

**Pre-requisites / Conditions (2 marks):**

1. There must be an **inheritance relationship** (parent–child).
2. The child class must **override** a method of the parent class.
3. The method must be called through a **parent class reference** pointing to a **child class object** (upcasting).

**Code Example (3 marks):**

```java
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal makes a sound");
    }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Cat meows");
    }
}
public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a;
        a = new Dog();
        a.sound();      // Dog's sound() invoked
        a = new Cat();
        a.sound();      // Cat's sound() invoked
    }
}
```

**Output:**  
```
Dog barks
Cat meows
```

---

**(b)** With a neat diagram, explain how **Dynamic Method Dispatch** is implemented using the **Virtual Method Table (vtable)** mechanism at runtime. Why are static methods not part of DMD? **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**Vtable Mechanism (4 marks):**  
Each class in Java has an associated **vtable** (virtual method table) that maps method signatures to actual method addresses in memory.  
- When a child class overrides a method, the **vtable entry** is updated to point to the **child's version**, while the **parent's vtable** remains unchanged.  
- At runtime, when `a.sound()` is called (where `a` is of type `Animal` but points to a `Dog` object), the JVM:
  1. Locates the object on the heap.
  2. Retrieves the object's vtable.
  3. Looks up the method `sound()` in the vtable.
  4. Invokes the address found — which is `Dog.sound()`.

**Diagram (1 mark):**
```
Parent Class Vtable          Child Class Vtable
+----------------+           +----------------+
| sound() -> 0xA1| (Parent)  | sound() -> 0xB2| (Child - overridden)
| eat()   -> 0xA2|           | eat()   -> 0xB3|
+----------------+           +----------------+
```

**Why Static Methods Excluded (2 marks):**  
Static methods belong to the **class**, not to any object. They are resolved by the compiler based on the **reference type** (compile-time binding). Since DMD operates on **instance methods** (which depend on object identity), static methods undergo **Method Hiding** rather than overriding and cannot be dynamically dispatched.

