        Shape s;   // Parent reference

        s = new Circle();
        s.draw();   // Dynamic dispatch -> Circle.draw()

        s = new Rectangle();
        s.draw();   // Dynamic dispatch -> Rectangle.draw()

        s = new Triangle();
        s.draw();   // Dynamic dispatch -> Triangle.draw()
    }
}
```

**Output:**  
```
Drawing a Circle: O
Drawing a Rectangle: []
Drawing a Triangle: /\
```

**Marks Distribution:** Class hierarchy (2), Override annotations (2), Upcasting + dynamic call demonstration (3).

---

**(b)** Explain why **instance variables are not polymorphically dispatched** in Java. Provide an example to support your answer. **(7 Marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**Explanation (4 marks):**  
In Java, **fields (instance variables)** are resolved at **compile time** based on the **reference variable's type**, not the actual object's type. This is because fields are not virtual in Java — there is no field-level vtable. The compiler resolves a field access using the declared type of the reference, ensuring type safety and avoiding the ambiguity that would arise if multiple classes declared fields with the same name but different types. Hence, only **methods** (specifically overridden instance methods) participate in dynamic dispatch, not variables.

**Example (3 marks):**

```java
class Father {
    int money = 5000;
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Father money: " + money);
    }
}
class Son extends Father {
    int money = 2000;  // Hides, not overrides
    @Override
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Son money: " + money);
    }
}
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Father f = new Son();
    System.out.println(f.money);  // 5000 (Father's money)
    f.show();                     // "Son money: 2000" (DMD on method)
}
```

**Key Observation:**  
- `f.money` → **5000** (compile-time binding to reference type `Father`).  
- `f.show()` → outputs `"Son money: 2000"` (runtime binding to object type `Son`).  

This contrast clearly proves that **methods are dynamically dispatched**, but **variables are not**.

---

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> **High-Density Revision Checklist — Dynamic Method Dispatch**

- **Definition:** Runtime resolution of overridden method calls based on the **actual object type**.  
- **Alternative names:** Late Binding, Runtime Binding, Runtime Polymorphism.  
- **Responsible entity:** **JVM (not the compiler)** decides which method to invoke.  
- **Three mandatory pre-requisites:** Inheritance, Method Overriding, Upcasting.  
- **Only instance methods** undergo DMD — static, private, final, and constructors do NOT.  
- **Instance variables are NEVER dynamically dispatched** — they are bound at compile time.  
- **Static methods** in inheritance undergo **Method Hiding** (compile-time binding).  
- **Upcasting syntax:** `Parent p = new Child();` — required for DMD demonstration.  
- **Vtable (Virtual Method Table):** Internal data structure used by JVM to track overridden method addresses.  
- **Performance implication:** Dynamic dispatch is marginally slower than static dispatch due to vtable lookup at runtime.  
- **Design principle alignment:** Supports **Open/Closed Principle** and **Dependency Inversion** in SOLID.  
- **Common exam trap:** Do not confuse **Overloading** (compile-time) with **Overriding** (runtime).  
- **Edge case:** Interfaces with `default` methods (Java 8+) also participate in DMD.  
- **Key phrase to use in exams:** *"The JVM dynamically binds the call to the method of the actual object type at runtime, achieving runtime polymorphism."*

