## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

In Object Oriented Programming, **exception handling** is a robust mechanism to detect, intercept, and gracefully recover from runtime errors (anomalous conditions) that disrupt the normal sequential flow of a program. The two foundational constructs of this mechanism are the **`try` block** and the **`catch` clause**.

* **try Block:** A *guarded* region of code, delimited by the keywords `try { ... }`, in which the programmer *anticipates* the possibility of an abnormal condition. The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) / C++ Runtime System *monitors* every statement inside this block. If an exception is *thrown* (either implicitly by the runtime or explicitly by the programmer using `throw`), the normal flow is immediately aborted, and control is transferred to the nearest matching handler.
* **catch Clause:** A *handler* (also called an *exception handler*) immediately following the `try` block, declared with the keyword `catch (ExceptionType identifier) { ... }`. It specifies the *type* of exception it can handle and contains the *recovery / reporting logic*. A catch clause is executed **only** when an exception of a matching type is thrown from within its associated try block.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Definition (Exact Board-Wording):**
> *"A `try` block encloses a set of statements in which an exception may occur. A `catch` clause is an exception handler that catches and handles a specific type of exception thrown from the preceding `try` block, thereby preventing program termination."*

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy – The "Trapeze + Safety Net" Model

Imagine a trapeze artist (the *risky code*) performing a high-flying stunt in a circus:

1. The **circus ring** is your `try` block — a controlled zone where a dangerous act is *permitted* because the act is expected to potentially fail.
2. The **safety net** stretched below is the `catch` clause — it does nothing during a *successful* stunt, but the moment the artist slips (an exception is thrown), the net instantly *catches* them and *absorbs* the impact (executes the recovery code).
3. If **no net** is present (no catch) and the artist falls, the show ends abruptly — analogous to a **program crash / abnormal termination**.

> [!NOTE]
> **Why do we need try-catch?** Without it, a single divide-by-zero, array out-of-bounds, or `null` pointer dereference terminates the entire program. With try-catch, the program **continues** after the error is handled — critical for banking, medical, and embedded systems.

### 1.3 Core Syntax Standards

**Java Standard Syntax (as per the official Java Language Specification, JLS §14.20):**

```java
try {
    // Statement 1
    // Statement 2   <-- monitored statements
    // Statement 3
} catch (ExceptionType1 e1) {
    // handler for ExceptionType1
} catch (ExceptionType2 e2) {
    // handler for ExceptionType2
} finally {
    // always executes (optional)
}
```

**C++ Standard Syntax (ISO C++17 / C++20):**

```cpp
try {
    // monitored statements
} catch (const std::exception& e) {
    // handler using standard exception
} catch (...) {
    // catch-all handler
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Strict Compiler Rule (KTU Pitfall):** In both Java and C++, a `try` block **cannot exist in isolation** — it must be followed by at least one `catch` clause or a `finally` (Java) block. Writing `try { }` alone is a **compilation error**.
