## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Structure Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Breakdown – The Three Phases

A try-catch construct operates in **three distinct phases**:

**Phase A — Setup (Compile Time)**
* The compiler verifies syntactical pairing: every `try` must be followed by `catch` (and optionally `finally`).
* It builds a *symbol table mapping* linking the `try` block to its associated handlers.
* The exception type declared in each `catch` parameter is registered in a *handler chain* (ordered list).

**Phase B — Execution (Runtime)**
* Program execution enters the `try` block statement-by-statement in **sequential order**.
* Each statement is monitored by the runtime exception monitor.
* If a statement executes successfully → flow proceeds to the next statement.
* If a statement *throws* an exception → the remaining statements of the `try` block are **skipped**, and the runtime searches the handler chain (top-down) for a **type-compatible catch clause**.

**Phase C — Recovery (Exception Resolution)**
* A catch clause is considered a *match* if the thrown exception object is `instanceof` (Java) or convertible to (C++) the parameter type.
* Once matched, that handler's body executes. **No other catch** is invoked (only one catch per exception, in the order of declaration).
* After the catch body completes, execution resumes at the line **after** the entire try-catch-finally construct.

### 2.2 Flow of Control – The Four Logical Cases

| Case | Condition | Behavior |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **C1** | `try` executes fully, no exception thrown | `catch` is **skipped entirely**; program continues normally after the block |
| **C2** | `try` throws an exception of type matching `catch` | The remaining statements of `try` are **skipped**; matching `catch` executes; program continues |
| **C3** | `try` throws an exception of **unmatched** type | The exception **propagates upward** to the enclosing try-catch (caller's frame); if no match found in the call stack → **program terminates abnormally** |
| **C4** | Exception is thrown **inside the catch block itself** | Handled by the **next** enclosing try-catch (or terminates if none) |

### 2.3 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet – try / catch Rules

| Rule | Java (JLS) | C++ (ISO) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Minimum pair** | `try` + at least one `catch` or `finally` | `try` + at least one `catch` |
| **Multiple catch order** | Most **specific** subclass **first**, parent class last | Most derived (specific) first |
| **Catch-all** | `catch (Exception e)` (since `Exception` is parent of all) | `catch (...)` (ellipsis — catches **everything**, including non-standard) |
| **Parameter type** | Must be `Throwable` subclass (checked) or any class | Can be **any copyable type**, including built-in (`int`, `const char*`) |
| **Parameter name** | Mandatory (`e`, `ex`, etc.) | Optional in C++: `catch (int)` is legal |
| **Re-throwing** | `throw;` inside catch re-throws same exception | `throw;` also re-throws |
| **Return in catch** | Allowed; `finally` still runs | Allowed; no finally equivalent |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU High-Yield Rule (Examiner's Favourite):** *In Java, a `catch (Exception e)` placed **before** `catch (ArithmeticException e)` causes a **compilation error** — unreachable code — because `ArithmeticException` is a subclass of `Exception` and the first handler would always match first.*

### 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Domain | Application of try-catch |
| :--- | :--- |
| **Banking Software** | Handles `InsufficientFundsException`, `InvalidAccountException` |
| **Embedded Systems (IoT)** | Catches sensor read failures, communication timeouts |
| **Network Programming** | Handles `SocketException`, `IOException` for resilience |
| **Database Systems** | Catches `SQLException`, `ConnectionFailureException` |
| **Aerospace / Avionics** | DO-178C standard mandates exception-safe code in flight control |
| **Medical Devices (FDA)** | IEC 62304 requires all runtime faults to be caught & logged |
