## 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Trace & Code Execution Flow

### 3.1 Exhaustive Trace – Worked Example (Java)

Consider the following program, a classic KTU-style question:

```java
public class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 10, b = 0, result;
        try {
            System.out.println("Statement 1");
            result = a / b;
            System.out.println("Statement 2");
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Statement 3: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        System.out.println("Statement 4");
    }
}
```

**Step-by-step trace:**

| Line | Action | Stack State | Output |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| 1 | `int a = 10, b = 0, result;` declared (uninitialised) | `a=10, b=0, result=?` | — |
| 2 | Enter `try` block; runtime monitoring begins | same | — |
| 3 | Execute `System.out.println("Statement 1")` | same | `Statement 1` |
| 4 | Evaluate `a / b` → `10 / 0` → JVM detects division by zero | exception object `ArithmeticException("/ by zero")` **thrown** | — |
| 5 | Runtime **skips** the rest of `try` (Statement 2 is **NOT** printed) | propagates out of try | — |
| 6 | Search handler chain: `catch (ArithmeticException e)` → **type matches** | handler entered; `e` refers to exception object | — |
| 7 | Execute `System.out.println("Statement 3: " + e.getMessage())` | same | `Statement 3: / by zero` |
| 8 | Exit catch block; flow continues after the entire try-catch | same | — |
| 9 | Execute `System.out.println("Statement 4")` | same | `Statement 4` |
| 10 | Program terminates **normally** | — | — |

**Final Console Output (exact order):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Statement 1} \\
\text{Statement 3: } \texttt{/ by zero} \\
\text{Statement 4}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Critical Observation:** `Statement 2` is **never printed** because the divide operation throws **before** it executes. This is the most-tested KTU concept.

### 3.2 Mathematical Representation of Control Flow

Let $T = \{t_1, t_2, \ldots, t_n\}$ be the set of statements in the `try` block, and $C = \{c_1, c_2, \ldots, c_m\}$ be the set of `catch` clauses with types $\tau_1, \tau_2, \ldots, \tau_m$. Let $e$ be the exception object thrown at statement $t_k$.

The control flow $F$ can be defined as:

$$
F = \begin{cases}
\text{execute}(t_n) \rightarrow \text{exit try-catch} & \text{if } e = \text{null (no exception)} \\[6pt]
\text{skip } \{t_{k+1}, \ldots, t_n\} \rightarrow \text{execute}(c_j) \text{ where } e \in \tau_j & \text{if } \exists j : e \in \tau_j \\[6pt]
\text{propagate } e \text{ to caller} & \text{if } \forall j : e \notin \tau_j
\end{cases}
$$

### 3.3 Exhaustive Trace – C++ Example (KTU 2024 Style)

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
    int x = 5, y = 0;
    try {
        if (y == 0)
            throw "Division by zero error";
        cout << "Result = " << (x / y) << endl;
    } catch (const char* msg) {
        cout << "Caught: " << msg << endl;
    }
    cout << "End of program" << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

**Trace:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text{Step 1: } x=5, y=0 \text{ initialised.} \\
& \text{Step 2: Enter try block; runtime monitor active.} \\
& \text{Step 3: } y == 0 \text{ evaluates to true.} \\
& \text{Step 4: } \texttt{throw "Division by zero error"} \text{ constructs a const char* literal and throws it.} \\
& \text{Step 5: Skip } \texttt{cout} \text{ line (unreachable for this execution).} \\
& \text{Step 6: Match found: } \texttt{catch (const char* msg)}. \\
& \text{Step 7: Print "Caught: Division by zero error".} \\
& \text{Step 8: Print "End of program".}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Output:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Caught: Division by zero error} \\
\text{End of program}
\end{aligned}
$$
