## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A – Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
> *Define a try block and a catch clause in Java. What happens if an exception is thrown inside a try block and is **not** caught by any of its associated catch handlers?*

**Model Answer (Examiner's Key Words in Bold):**

A **`try` block** is a *guarded region* in Java that encloses statements which may throw an exception. A **`catch` clause** is an *exception handler* attached to a try block that specifies the type of exception it can handle and contains the recovery code.

If an exception is thrown inside a `try` block and **no matching `catch`** is found, then the exception is **propagated up the call stack** to the enclosing method. If no method in the call stack handles it, the **JVM terminates the program abnormally** and prints a *stack trace* to the standard error stream (`System.err`).

---

> **Q2. [KTU University Exam – June 2024]**
> *Explain why a `try` block in Java cannot exist without a `catch` (or `finally`) block. What is the role of the `finally` block when attached after a try-catch?*

**Model Answer:**

According to the **Java Language Specification (§14.20)**, a `try` statement must have a `catch` and/or a `finally` block. This is because a try block on its own has **no semantic meaning** — the compiler enforces this rule to prevent *orphaned guarded regions* that would silently swallow exceptions or, worse, leave them unhandled.

A **`finally` block**, when present, contains code that executes **unconditionally** — whether an exception is thrown, caught, or not thrown at all. It is conventionally used for **resource cleanup** (closing files, releasing database connections, freeing network sockets), guaranteeing cleanup even on abnormal exit.

---

