> ### **Question B (14 Marks) – [KTU University Exam – June 2024 Model]**
>
> **(a)** Differentiate between **checked exceptions** and **unchecked exceptions** in Java. How does the `try-catch` mechanism differ for each category? Provide one example for each. **(7 Marks)**
>
> **(b)** Write a Java program that defines a method `divide(int a, int b)` which **throws** an `ArithmeticException` if `b == 0`. Demonstrate it being called from `main` inside a `try-catch` block, and explain the control flow. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### Model Solution for (a):

| Feature | Checked Exceptions | Unchecked Exceptions |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Inheritance** | Subclass of `Exception` (not `RuntimeException`) | Subclass of `RuntimeException` (or `Error`) |
| **Compile-time check** | Compiler **forces** handling (`try-catch` or `throws`) | Compiler **does not force** handling |
| **Cause** | External resources (files, DB, network) | Programming bugs (logic errors) |
| **try-catch required?** | **Mandatory** for compilation | **Optional** but recommended |
| **Example 1** | `IOException` | `ArithmeticException` |
| **Example 2** | `SQLException` | `NullPointerException` |
| **Example 3** | `FileNotFoundException` | `ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException` |

**For checked exceptions**, the compiler **enforces** a `try-catch` (or a `throws` declaration in the method signature). If neither is present → **compilation error**. Example:

```java
// Checked - try-catch mandatory
try {
    FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
} catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
    System.out.println("File missing!");
}
```

**For unchecked exceptions**, the compiler does **not** enforce handling. You may write the code without try-catch and it will compile, but if the exception occurs at runtime and is unhandled, the program crashes. Example:

```java
// Unchecked - try-catch optional but wise
int x = 10 / 0;   // compiles fine, crashes at runtime
```

#### Model Solution for (b):

```java
public class ThrowDemo {

    // Method declares it may throw an exception
    static int divide(int a, int b) throws ArithmeticException {
        if (b == 0) {
            throw new ArithmeticException("Cannot divide by zero");
        }
        return a / b;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            System.out.println("Result1: " + divide(10, 2));
            System.out.println("Result2: " + divide(10, 0));   // throws here
            System.out.println("Result3: " + divide(20, 4));   // NOT reached
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught in main: " + e.getMessage());
        }
        System.out.println("Program continues...");
    }
}
```

**Output:**

```
Result1: 5
Caught in main: Cannot divide by zero
Program continues...
```

**Control Flow Explanation:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text{1. main() calls } \texttt{divide(10, 2)} \rightarrow \text{returns 5, prints "Result1: 5"}. \\
& \text{2. main() calls } \texttt{divide(10, 0)} \rightarrow \text{method checks } b==0 \rightarrow \text{throws new ArithmeticException}. \\
& \text{3. The throw causes the call stack to unwind: divide() exits abnormally.} \\
& \text{4. Back in main(), the exception is caught by } \texttt{catch (ArithmeticException e)}. \\
& \text{5. The line } \texttt{Result3} \text{ is NEVER reached (similar to skip behaviour in try).} \\
& \text{6. After catch, "Program continues..." is printed.} \\
& \text{7. main() returns; JVM exits normally.}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!WARNING]
> **Examiner's Pitfall – Q5(b):**
> * **Forgetting `throws` clause in method signature:** If `divide()` is declared to `throw` an exception but the method signature lacks `throws ArithmeticException`, the compiler may allow it (since `ArithmeticException` is unchecked), but examiners **deduct 1 mark** for stylistic inconsistency.
> * **Not labelling "Result3 is NOT reached":** Examiners specifically look for students demonstrating awareness of the **skip-after-throw** behaviour. Missing this explanation = 1 mark lost.

