## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 The `throws` Keyword

**Formal Definition:**
The `throws` keyword in Java is a **declarative clause** attached to a method's signature. It explicitly announces to the compiler (and to any caller of the method) that the method body may **propagate one or more checked exceptions** back to the calling environment rather than handling them internally. It does not *throw* the exception itself; it merely *advertises* the possibility of propagation, shifting the exception-handling responsibility up the call stack.

```java
accessModifier returnType methodName(parameterList) throws ExceptionType1, ExceptionType2 {
    // method body
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** The `throws` clause is a compile-time contract, not a runtime mechanism. It is **mandatory** for checked exceptions (e.g., `IOException`, `SQLException`, `ClassNotFoundException`) and **optional** for unchecked exceptions (e.g., `ArithmeticException`, `NullPointerException`).

### 1.2 The `finally` Block

**Formal Definition:**
The `finally` block is an **optional but highly recommended** code segment that follows `try` (and optionally `catch`) blocks. It contains code that **must execute regardless of whether an exception was thrown, caught, or even if the program attempts to exit the try block early via `return`, `break`, or `continue`**. Its primary purpose is to release system resources such as file handles, database connections, network sockets, and memory locks.

```java
try {
    // protected code
} catch (ExceptionType e) {
    // handler
} finally {
    // cleanup code — always runs
}
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Key Principle:** The JVM guarantees that a `finally` block will execute *before* the method returns control to its caller, even in catastrophic situations — **with only three exceptions**: (1) `System.exit(0)` is invoked, (2) the JVM crashes, (3) an infinite loop or `Thread.stop()` occurs in the try block.

### 1.3 Conceptual Analogy

**Analogy for `throws` — The Restaurant Menu Disclaimer:**
Imagine you walk into a restaurant. Before you order, the menu clearly states: *"This dish may contain nuts. If you are allergic, please inform the waiter."* The kitchen is not serving you nuts; it is merely **declaring the risk upfront**. If you are allergic (the caller cannot handle it), you (the caller) must take precautions — either avoid the dish or carry an EpiPen (`try-catch`). The `throws` clause works exactly like this: it is a *public health notice* on a method's contract.

**Analogy for `finally` — The Airplane Landing Sequence:**
Regardless of whether your flight was smooth, turbulent, or had a medical emergency mid-air, the pilot **must** perform a post-flight checklist: engines off, doors disarmed, logbook signed, fuel recorded. Even if the flight is **diverted, cancelled, or arrives normally**, the checklist (cleanup) runs. The `finally` block is the pilot's post-flight checklist — it runs **no matter what happened during the flight**.

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Engineering Utility:** In JDBC database programming, `finally` is the gold-standard location for closing `Connection`, `Statement`, and `ResultSet` objects to prevent resource leaks. In socket programming, it ensures ports are released. This is why KTU examiners frequently test this concept with I/O and database code.

