# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition

In the Java **Swing** API (part of the Java Foundation Classes – JFC, located in the package `javax.swing`), **buttons** are interactive GUI components that allow the user to initiate an action, toggle a state, or select one or more options. They are descendants of the abstract class `javax.swing.AbstractButton`, which itself extends `java.awt.Component` and implements the `java.awt.ItemSelectable` interface. The four primary concrete button classes in Swing that a KTU 2024 OOP student must master are:

- `javax.swing.JButton` — a **command button** that fires an `ActionEvent` when clicked.
- `javax.swing.JToggleButton` — a **two-state button** (pressed/released) that stays selected until clicked again.
- `javax.swing.JCheckBox` — a **multi-selection toggle** typically used to enable/disable independent options.
- `javax.swing.JRadioButton` — a **single-selection toggle** that, when grouped using `javax.swing.ButtonGroup`, allows only one option to be selected at a time.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** Questions in the End Semester Examination (ESE) frequently test the **class hierarchy** (`AbstractButton` → concrete button classes), the correct use of **`ButtonGroup`**, and the distinction between **`ActionEvent`** (fired by `JButton`) and **`ItemEvent`** (fired by toggle-style buttons).

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine the front panel of a **microwave oven**:

- The **Start / Stop / Cancel** keys correspond to a `JButton`. You press them, the action happens, and the button springs back to its original position immediately.
- The **Grill** switch (which stays "in" when pressed and clicks "out" when pressed again) is a `JToggleButton` — it has a memory.
- The checkboxes next to *"Child Lock"*, *"Sound"*, and *"Clock Display"* are `JCheckBox`es — you can tick any number of them independently.
- The round selector knob where you choose between **Micro / Grill / Convection** represents `JRadioButton`s — only one mode can be active at any time, so the manufacturer logically groups them inside a single `ButtonGroup`.

## 1.3 Standard Metrics & Properties

Every Swing button exposes a common set of **bean properties** inherited from `AbstractButton` and `JComponent`. The following table lists the most exam-relevant ones. All values are expressed in standard **pixels** unless noted.

| Property (Type) | Default | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `text` (`String`) | `""` (empty) | Caption displayed on the button. |
| `icon` (`Icon`) | `null` | Graphic shown on the button. |
| `mnemonic` (`char`) | none | Keyboard shortcut (combined with the platform modifier). |
| `toolTipText` (`String`) | `null` | Hover text. |
| `selected` (`boolean`) | `false` | Current pressed-state (toggle-style buttons only). |
| `enabled` (`boolean`) | `true` | Whether the button responds to input. |

> [!NOTE]
> **Constants for Key Bindings:** Swing buttons fire events whose IDs are static integer constants such as `ActionEvent.ACTION_PERFORMED`, `ItemEvent.SELECTED`, and `ItemEvent.DESELECTED`. Always use the constants in the `if` checks — never the numeric value (which is implementation-specific and loses marks in KTU valuations).
