# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 Class Hierarchy (Why It Matters)

The hierarchy is the single most important diagram you can draw for a KTU OOP exam. It demonstrates the **"is-a"** OOP relationship and shows why every Swing button shares the same `setText()`, `setIcon()`, `addActionListener()`, and `setEnabled()` methods.

```text
java.lang.Object
   └── java.awt.Component
         └── java.awt.Container
               └── javax.swing.JComponent
                     └── javax.swing.AbstractButton  (abstract)
                           ├── javax.swing.JButton
                           ├── javax.swing.JToggleButton
                           │      ├── javax.swing.JCheckBox
                           │      └── javax.swing.JRadioButton
                           └── javax.swing.JMenuItem
```

**Why this hierarchy?**
1. **Code reuse** — common code (e.g., icon/text handling) is written *once* in `AbstractButton`.
2. **Polymorphism** — a method can accept an `AbstractButton` argument and work for *all* four concrete subclasses.
3. **Specialisation** — `JToggleButton` adds a *state* (`selected` boolean), which `JButton` lacks.

## 2.2 The Four Buttons — Operational Logic

### 2.2.1 `JButton` — The Command Trigger

- **Logic:** When the user releases the mouse button **inside** the component bounds, an `ActionEvent` is dispatched to every registered `ActionListener`.
- **Key Constructors:**
  - `JButton()` — empty button.
  - `JButton(String text)` — button with caption.
  - `JButton(Icon icon)` — button with graphic.
  - `JButton(String text, Icon icon)` — caption + graphic.
- **Primary Event:** `java.awt.event.ActionEvent` (constant `ACTION_PERFORMED`).
- **Listener Interface:** `java.awt.event.ActionListener` (single method `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`).

### 2.2.2 `JToggleButton` — The Sticky Switch

- Adds the property `selected` (`boolean`). The button retains its pressed visual state until clicked again.
- Implements `ItemSelectable`, so it can fire `ItemEvent`s in addition to `ActionEvent`s.
- **Use-case:** *Bold*, *Italic*, *Underline* toggles in a text editor toolbar.

### 2.2.3 `JCheckBox` — Multi-Select Toggle

- A `JToggleButton` with a **checkbox** look-and-feel.
- Multiple checkboxes in a form are **independent** — they are *not* placed inside a `ButtonGroup`.
- **Event:** `ItemEvent` (use `ItemListener.itemStateChanged`).

### 2.2.4 `JRadioButton` — Mutually Exclusive Toggle

- A `JToggleButton` with a **radio circle** look-and-feel.
- To enforce mutual exclusion, you **must** add the radio buttons to a single `javax.swing.ButtonGroup` object using `group.add(radioButton)`.
- Without a `ButtonGroup`, radio buttons behave like independent checkboxes — a classic KTU pitfall.

## 2.3 ButtonGroup — The Logical Container

`ButtonGroup` is a **non-visual** container (it does not appear on the screen; do not add it to a `JFrame` or `JPanel`). It enforces the *one-selected-at-a-time* policy among its member buttons, regardless of where those buttons are physically placed in the container hierarchy.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`ButtonGroup` only manages selection state.** It does **not** lay out components. You must still add each `JRadioButton` to a visible container (`JPanel`, `JFrame`, etc.). Forgetting the latter is the most common error and warrants a 1-mark deduction per KTU valuation keys.

## 2.4 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

| Class | Mutually Exclusive? | Event Fired | Listener Interface | Logical Container |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `JButton` | N/A (command) | `ActionEvent` | `ActionListener` | — |
| `JToggleButton` | N/A (sticky) | `ActionEvent` + `ItemEvent` | Both | Optional `ButtonGroup` |
| `JCheckBox` | No (independent) | `ItemEvent` (primary) | `ItemListener` | — |
| `JRadioButton` | Yes (when grouped) | `ItemEvent` (primary) | `ItemListener` | `ButtonGroup` (mandatory) |

## 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **HMI / SCADA Panels:** Industrial operator screens (factory PLCs, medical device UIs) use Swing buttons to acknowledge alarms, start/stop motors, and toggle auto/manual modes.
- **Telecom Configuration Tools:** Radio buttons are used to select a single communication protocol (TCP / UDP / Serial) from mutually exclusive options.
- **Raspberry-Pi / Embedded Java GUIs:** Swing remains portable and lightweight for kiosk-style interfaces running on single-board computers.
