# 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Walkthroughs

## 3.1 Walkthrough A — Creating and Handling a `JButton`

The following Java program demonstrates the **canonical pattern** for any Swing button: *create → add listener → add to container*. Each step below corresponds to a comment in the code.

```java
import javax.swing.JButton;
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JOptionPane;
import java.awt.FlowLayout;
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;

public class ButtonDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JButton b1, b2;

    public ButtonDemo() {
        // Step 1: Instantiate buttons with captions
        b1 = new JButton("Click Me");
        b2 = new JButton("Exit");

        // Step 2: Register the frame as a listener for both
        b1.addActionListener(this);
        b2.addActionListener(this);

        // Step 3: Add buttons to the content pane
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        add(b1);
        add(b2);

        // Step 4: Frame boilerplate
        setSize(300, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    // Step 5: The single callback method receives every event.
    // Use getSource() to identify which button fired it.
    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        Object src = e.getSource();
        if (src == b1) {
            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, "Hello from b1!");
        } else if (src == b2) {
            System.exit(0);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new ButtonDemo();
    }
}
```

**Explanation of the key lines**

- `b1.addActionListener(this);` — The frame *implements* `ActionListener`, so passing `this` is valid. A separate inner/anonymous class is also acceptable.
- `e.getSource()` returns an `Object` that you compare against the specific button reference. Comparing the `ActionCommand` string (set via `b.setActionCommand("EXIT")`) is the more robust alternative.
- `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` — Without this line, closing the window does **not** terminate the JVM, and your program hangs.

## 3.2 Walkthrough B — `JCheckBox` and `JToggleButton` Using `ItemEvent`

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class CheckToggleDemo extends JFrame implements ItemListener {
    JCheckBox cbBold, cbItalic;
    JToggleButton tbUnderline;
    JLabel result;

    public CheckToggleDemo() {
        cbBold       = new JCheckBox("Bold");
        cbItalic     = new JCheckBox("Italic");
        tbUnderline  = new JToggleButton("Underline");
        result       = new JLabel("Style: ");

        cbBold.addItemListener(this);
        cbItalic.addItemListener(this);
        tbUnderline.addItemListener(this);

        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        add(cbBold); add(cbItalic); add(tbUnderline); add(result);
        setSize(400, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e) {
        String style = "Style: ";
        if (cbBold.isSelected())    style += "Bold ";
        if (cbItalic.isSelected())  style += "Italic ";
        if (tbUnderline.isSelected()) style += "Underline ";
        result.setText(style);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) { new CheckToggleDemo(); }
}
```

**Why `isSelected()` and not `e.getStateChange()`?**

Both are valid. The `ItemEvent.getStateChange()` method returns either `ItemEvent.SELECTED` or `ItemEvent.DESELECTED` (constants). `isSelected()` is a *post-event* query on the model and is generally cleaner when your logic depends on the **combined** state of multiple toggles (as above).

## 3.3 Walkthrough C — `JRadioButton` with `ButtonGroup` (Mutual Exclusion)

The following derivation shows exactly how a `ButtonGroup` enforces a single selection. We will add **three** radio buttons; only one can be selected at any moment.

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class RadioGroupDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JRadioButton r1, r2, r3;
    ButtonGroup group;
    JLabel display;

    public RadioGroupDemo() {
        // Step 1: Create the radio buttons
        r1 = new JRadioButton("Red");
        r2 = new JRadioButton("Green");
        r3 = new JRadioButton("Blue");

        // Step 2: Create a non-visual ButtonGroup
        group = new ButtonGroup();
        group.add(r1);
        group.add(r2);
        group.add(r3);

        // Step 3: Visually add the buttons to the JFrame
        // NOTE: ButtonGroup itself is NOT added to the frame.
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        add(r1); add(r2); add(r3);
        display = new JLabel("Pick a colour");
        add(display);

        // Step 4: Listeners (ActionEvent is convenient here)
        r1.addActionListener(this);
        r2.addActionListener(this);
        r3.addActionListener(this);

        setSize(300, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // Use getActionCommand() — returns the text label by default
        String colour = ((JRadioButton) e.getSource()).getActionCommand();
        display.setText("Selected: " + colour);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) { new RadioGroupDemo(); }
}
```

**Analytical Notes**
- Removing the `group.add(...)` lines turns this code into three *independent* checkboxes visually — a classic KTU viva question.
- `getActionCommand()` defaults to the button's `text`. You can override it with `r1.setActionCommand("RED")` if you want labels to differ from displayed text.
- All three buttons are inside the same `ButtonGroup`, so clicking `r2` automatically deselects `r1` and `r3`. The **model** maintains this; the developer does not need to write any code to deselect manually.

## 3.4 Mnemonic and Action Command Cheat Derivation

A mnemonic is an underlined character used as a keyboard shortcut. It is set by:

$$\texttt{button.setMnemonic(KeyEvent.VK\_B)}$$

The accelerator is the **key combination** (e.g., `Ctrl + B`) registered through the button's `Action` object. For exam purposes, remember the order: *set text first → then mnemonic*. If you set a mnemonic for a character that is not in the text, the key shortcut will still work but no letter is visually underlined.
