    jtbA --> jcbA
    jtbA --> jrbA
    bgA -. enforces .-> jrbA
```

> **Reading the diagram:** Solid arrows denote `extends` (inheritance). The dashed arrow denotes a *logical* relationship — `ButtonGroup` is **not** a superclass of `JRadioButton`; it merely manages its selection state.

## 4.2 Block-Level Architecture — Button Interaction Lifecycle

The following block diagram captures the **runtime flow** when a user clicks any Swing button. It replaces a literal event-flowchart with a clean architectural view.

```mermaid
graph TD
    userA[USER]
    uiA[GUI Layer JButton or JCheckBox or JRadioButton]
    evA[Event Dispatch Thread EDT]
    alA[ActionListener or ItemListener]
    mlA[Model Layer ButtonModel]
    rpA[Application Response]

    userA -->|mouse press or release| uiA
    uiA -->|fires ActionEvent or ItemEvent| evA
    evA -->|invokes callback| alA
    alA -->|reads or updates| mlA
    mlA -->|notifies peers| uiA
    alA -->|business logic| rpA
    rpA -->|feedback string or icon| uiA
```

> **Engineering insight:** Every GUI event travels through the **Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)**. Long-running operations (file I/O, network) should *not* be executed inside the listener callback, or the UI will freeze. This is the **Swing single-thread rule**, frequently tested in viva voce.

## 4.3 Mental Map: When to Use Which Button

