# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Q1. Differentiate between `JButton` and `JToggleButton`. Mention the event each one fires. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, Model Paper 2]

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

| Aspect | `JButton` | `JToggleButton` |
|---|---|---|
| State memory | None — springs back after release | Two states — `selected` / `not selected` |
| Primary event | `ActionEvent` (on release inside bounds) | `ItemEvent` (on every state change); also `ActionEvent` |
| Use case | Start, Save, Cancel, Submit | Bold, Italic, Mute toggle |
| Mutually exclusive grouping | Not applicable | Optional via `ButtonGroup` |

(1 mark for state difference, 1 mark for event types, 1 mark for example/use case.)

---

### Q2. Why is a `ButtonGroup` *not* added to a container like `JFrame` or `JPanel`? [KTU University Exam – May 2024, Supple]

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
`ButtonGroup` is a **non-visual logical container**. Its single responsibility is to enforce a one-of-many selection policy among the toggle buttons added to it (`add(AbstractButton b)`). Because it has no visual representation, attempting to add it to a `JFrame` or `JPanel` would either be ignored by the layout manager or result in a compile-time error (`ButtonGroup` is not a subclass of `Component`). The individual `JRadioButton` instances must still be added to a *visible* container so the user can see and click them. (2 marks for the non-visual reason, 1 mark for the requirement to add each radio button to a visible container.)

