## 5.2 Part B — Module Internal Choice (14 Marks Each)

### Question A (14 Marks) — JButton + JCheckBox Application

**(a)** Write a Java Swing program that contains a `JButton` labelled **"Submit"** and three `JCheckBox`es for the languages *English*, *Hindi*, and *Malayalam*. When the user clicks **Submit**, display a `JOptionPane` message listing the languages the user has ticked. **[**7 marks**]**

**(b)** Explain the role of the `ActionListener` interface in your program. Why is `e.getSource()` used inside `actionPerformed`? **[**7 marks**]**

#### Model Solution

**Part (a) — 7 marks**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class LanguageSelector extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JCheckBox cbEng, cbHin, cbMal;
    JButton submit;
    JLabel hint;

    public LanguageSelector() {
        cbEng = new JCheckBox("English");
        cbHin = new JCheckBox("Hindi");
        cbMal = new JCheckBox("Malayalam");
        submit = new JButton("Submit");
        hint   = new JLabel("Tick at least one option");

        submit.addActionListener(this);

        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        add(cbEng); add(cbHin); add(cbMal); add(submit); add(hint);
        setSize(350, 180);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == submit) {
            String msg = "You selected: ";
            if (cbEng.isSelected()) msg += "English ";
            if (cbHin.isSelected()) msg += "Hindi ";
            if (cbMal.isSelected()) msg += "Malayalam ";
            if (msg.equals("You selected: "))
                msg = "No language selected!";
            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, msg);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) { new LanguageSelector(); }
}
```

**Mark split:** 2 marks for correct instantiation and layout, 2 marks for `addActionListener` registration, 2 marks for the `isSelected()` logic, 1 mark for `JOptionPane` and frame boilerplate.

**Part (b) — 7 marks**

The `ActionListener` interface (located in `java.awt.event`) declares a single callback method `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`. Swing components (such as `JButton`) call this method on every registered listener when a user action occurs. (2 marks)

In this program, the **frame** implements `ActionListener` and is registered with the `submit` button using `submit.addActionListener(this)`. This is an application of the **Observer design pattern** (OOP Module 1 / 2 context): the button is the *Subject*, the frame is the *Observer*. (2 marks)

`e.getSource()` is used because the same callback method can be registered to **multiple** event sources. It returns the `Object` reference of the component that fired the event, allowing the listener to **dispatch** behaviour based on the originator (e.g., distinguishing between "Submit" and a future "Reset" button sharing the same handler). (2 marks)

Alternative: setting `submit.setActionCommand("SUBMIT")` and comparing `e.getActionCommand()` provides a more loosely coupled dispatcher that survives object recreation. (1 mark)

