### Question B (14 Marks) — JRadioButton + ButtonGroup Application

**(a)** Develop a Java Swing program that displays three `JRadioButton`s — *Male*, *Female*, *Other* — grouped inside a `ButtonGroup`, plus a `JButton` labelled **"Show"**. Clicking **Show** must display the selected gender in a `JLabel`. **[**7 marks**]**

**(b)** What happens if you forget to add the radio buttons to a `ButtonGroup`? Justify your answer with reference to Swing's MVC design. **[**7 marks**]**

#### Model Solution

**Part (a) — 7 marks**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class GenderSelector extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JRadioButton rMale, rFemale, rOther;
    ButtonGroup group;
    JButton show;
    JLabel result;

    public GenderSelector() {
        rMale   = new JRadioButton("Male");
        rFemale = new JRadioButton("Female");
        rOther  = new JRadioButton("Other");
        group   = new ButtonGroup();
        group.add(rMale);
        group.add(rFemale);
        group.add(rOther);

        show   = new JButton("Show");
        result = new JLabel("No selection");
        show.addActionListener(this);

        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        add(rMale); add(rFemale); add(rOther); add(show); add(result);

        setSize(350, 180);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == show) {
            String choice = "No selection";
            if (rMale.isSelected())   choice = "Male";
            if (rFemale.isSelected()) choice = "Female";
            if (rOther.isSelected())  choice = "Other";
            result.setText("Selected: " + choice);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) { new GenderSelector(); }
}
```

**Mark split:** 2 marks `ButtonGroup` creation and `add` calls, 2 marks radio button instantiation, 2 marks `actionPerformed` dispatch logic, 1 mark layout and frame boilerplate.

**Part (b) — 7 marks**

Swing follows the **Model-View-Controller (MVC)** architecture (more precisely, *Separable Model Architecture* in Swing). Each component is split into:

- **Model** (`ButtonModel`) — holds the state, e.g., `isSelected()`.
- **View** (the `UIResource` / Look-and-Feel delegate) — renders the circles and the caption.
- **Controller** (event listeners) — reacts to user input. (2 marks)

When three `JRadioButton`s are **not** placed inside a `ButtonGroup`, each radio button is paired with its **own independent `ButtonModel`**. Hence, the user can mark *Male*, *Female*, and *Other* **simultaneously**, defeating the very purpose of a radio button. (2 marks)

When the three buttons are added to a **single** `ButtonGroup`, Swing's `ButtonGroup` class internally maintains a `Vector` of `ButtonModel` references and forces the `setSelected(true)` call on one model to call `setSelected(false)` on every other model. This is **enforced at the model layer**, not by any code the developer writes. (2 marks)

Therefore, forgetting the `ButtonGroup` does *not* cause a compile-time or runtime error — the program runs, but behaves incorrectly. This is why KTU examiners deduct a full 2 marks: the program "works" syntactically but fails the logical requirement. (1 mark)

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls**
> 1. **Forgetting `setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE)`** — Window closes but JVM keeps running; examiner deducts 1 mark.
> 2. **Adding `ButtonGroup` to the frame's content pane** — Layout manager ignores it silently; the student thinks grouping works. Deduct 2 marks.
> 3. **Using numeric values in event comparisons** (e.g., `if (e.getID() == 1001)`) — Always use the constants `ActionEvent.ACTION_PERFORMED` and `ItemEvent.SELECTED` / `ItemEvent.DESELECTED`. Deduct 1 mark.
> 4. **Confusing `JButton` with `JToggleButton`** — Writing `b.setSelected(true)` on a `JButton` compiles (the method is inherited from `AbstractButton`) but does nothing visually. The student loses 2 marks.
> 5. **Not calling `setVisible(true)`** — The window never appears; the examiner cannot test the logic. Deduct 1 mark.

