## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Class root:** Every Swing button inherits from `javax.swing.AbstractButton`.
- **Command button:** `JButton` → fires `ActionEvent` → implement `ActionListener`.
- **Toggle family:** `JToggleButton` → `JCheckBox` (multi) and `JRadioButton` (single when grouped) → primarily fire `ItemEvent` → implement `ItemListener`.
- **`ButtonGroup` is non-visual** — never add it to a container; only add the toggle buttons to it.
- **Default selection state** of every toggle button is `false`; explicitly call `setSelected(true)` if you want a pre-selected default.
- **Event identification:** prefer `e.getActionCommand()` (string) over `e.getSource()` (object reference) for decoupled dispatch.
- **Mnemonics:** set via `setMnemonic(KeyEvent.VK_x)`; the corresponding character should appear in the button's `text`.
- **Threading rule:** all Swing event handling occurs on the **Event Dispatch Thread** (EDT); never call `Thread.sleep()` inside a listener.
- **Polymorphism in action:** a method declared `void doSomething(AbstractButton b)` accepts *any* of the four button types — frequently asked in Part A.
- **The `Action` interface:** advanced topic — a single `javax.swing.Action` object can be shared by a `JButton`, a `JMenuItem`, and a toolbar button, ensuring all three have identical state (text, icon, enabled, tooltip). High-yield for KTU Module 4 viva.
- **Disabling a button** with `setEnabled(false)` greys it out *and* prevents any events from firing — useful for enforcing pre-conditions (e.g., "Save" disabled until a file path is chosen).
