### 3.2 Exhaustive Worked Example 1 — A Simple JTextField with ActionListener

Below is a fully annotated, line-by-line explanation of a complete program.

**Problem Statement:** Create a Swing application with a `JTextField` and a `JLabel`. When the user types text into the field and presses Enter, the label should display the same text prefixed with "You entered: ".

**Code Listing:**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class TextFieldDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    JTextField textField;
    JLabel label;

    public TextFieldDemo() {
        setTitle("JTextField Event Handling Demo");
        setSize(400, 150);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        textField = new JTextField(20);     // (1) Create field with 20 columns
        label = new JLabel("Type and press Enter");

        textField.addActionListener(this);  // (2) Register this frame as listener

        add(textField);
        add(label);

        setVisible(true);                   // (3) Display the GUI
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // (4) Logic executed when Enter is pressed
        String input = textField.getText();
        label.setText("You entered: " + input);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new TextFieldDemo();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace:**

1. **Line `(1)` — `JTextField(20)` is created:** The constructor sets the column count to **20** (the visual width hint in `em`-based character cells). The initial text is empty.
2. **Line `(2)` — `addActionListener(this)`:** The frame (which implements `ActionListener`) is registered with the `textField`. Internally, `JTextField` stores `this` in its `EventListenerList`.
3. **Line `(3)` — `setVisible(true)`:** The window is rendered, and Swing starts dispatching events on the EDT.
4. **Line `(4)` — `actionPerformed` is invoked:** When the user presses Enter inside the text field, Swing creates an `ActionEvent` and calls the `actionPerformed` method on every registered listener (in this case, only the frame). The handler reads the text using `getText()` and updates the label using `setText()`.

---

### 3.3 Exhaustive Worked Example 2 — JTextField with KeyListener (Adapter Approach)

**Problem Statement:** When the user types the letter 'A' (uppercase or lowercase) in a `JTextField`, append `*` to a `JTextArea`. Otherwise, append the typed character.

**Code Listing:**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class KeyAdapterDemo extends JFrame {
    JTextField textField;
    JTextArea textArea;

    public KeyAdapterDemo() {
        setTitle("KeyAdapter with JTextField");
        setSize(400, 300);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        textField = new JTextField(15);
        textArea = new JTextArea(10, 30);
        textArea.setEditable(false);

        // Use anonymous inner class extending KeyAdapter
        textField.addKeyListener(new KeyAdapter() {
            @Override
            public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) {
                char c = e.getKeyChar();
                if (c == 'A' || c == 'a') {
                    textArea.append("*\n");
                } else {
                    textArea.append(c + "\n");
                }
            }
        });

        add(textField);
        add(new JScrollPane(textArea));
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new KeyAdapterDemo();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace:**

1. **KeyAdapter Selection** — Rather than implementing `KeyListener` (which would require defining three empty methods), the program extends `KeyAdapter` and overrides only `keyTyped`. This is the **adapter pattern** in action.
2. **Listener Registration** — An anonymous instance of the adapter is registered with `textField` via `addKeyListener()`.
3. **Event Flow** — On every keystroke, Swing fires a `KeyEvent`. The adapter's `keyTyped` method is invoked.
4. **Character Logic** — If the typed character is 'A' or 'a', a `*` is appended to the text area; otherwise, the character itself is appended.
5. **CaretEvent / FocusEvent Optional** — Note that pressing Enter would additionally fire an `ActionEvent` on the `JTextField`. If both `KeyListener` and `ActionListener` are registered, both will fire, in that order.

---

### 3.4 Exhaustive Worked Example 3 — DocumentListener for Real-Time Text Validation

**Problem Statement:** As the user types in a `JTextField`, validate that the input is a number. If not, display "Invalid" in a `JLabel`.

**Code Listing:**

```java
import javax.swing.*;
import javax.swing.event.*;
import java.awt.*;

public class DocListenerDemo extends JFrame {
    JTextField textField;
    JLabel statusLabel;

    public DocListenerDemo() {
        setTitle("DocumentListener Demo");
        setSize(350, 120);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

        textField = new JTextField(15);
        statusLabel = new JLabel("Start typing...");

        textField.getDocument().addDocumentListener(new DocumentListener() {
            public void insertUpdate(DocumentEvent e) { validate(); }
            public void removeUpdate(DocumentEvent e) { validate(); }
            public void changedUpdate(DocumentEvent e) { validate(); }
            private void validate() {
                String s = textField.getText();
                if (s.matches("\\d*")) {
                    statusLabel.setText("Valid: " + s);
                } else {
                    statusLabel.setText("Invalid: not a number");
                }
            }
        });

        add(textField);
        add(statusLabel);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new DocListenerDemo();
    }
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace:**

1. **`getDocument()`** — Returns the `javax.swing.text.Document` backing the `JTextField`. This is where text changes are recorded.
2. **DocumentListener Registration** — Three callbacks (`insertUpdate`, `removeUpdate`, `changedUpdate`) are required because all three are abstract in the `DocumentListener` interface.
3. **Validation Logic** — A regular expression `\d*` (zero or more digits) is used to test the current text.
4. **Real-Time Feedback** — Every keystroke triggers one of the three callbacks, which in turn call `validate()` and update the label.

---

### 3.5 Analytical Matrix — Listener Registration Syntax Patterns

| Pattern | Code | Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| Implementing interface in same class | `class MyFrame extends JFrame implements ActionListener { ... }` | Single-listener, simple GUIs |
| Anonymous inner class | `btn.addActionListener(new ActionListener() { public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) { ... } });` | Quick one-off handlers |
| Lambda expression (Java 8+) | `btn.addActionListener(e -> label.setText("Clicked"));` | Functional style, valid since `ActionListener` is `@FunctionalInterface` |
| Named inner class | `class MyHandler implements ActionListener { ... }` then `btn.addActionListener(new MyHandler());` | Reusable handlers |
| Adapter subclass | `class MyKeyAdapter extends KeyAdapter { ... }` | Multi-method listeners where only some methods are needed |

> [!NOTE]
> Since `ActionListener` has exactly one abstract method (`actionPerformed`), it qualifies as a **functional interface** and can be targeted by a **lambda expression**. The lambda is the most concise KTU-recommended modern style.

---

### 3.6 Worked Lambda Variant of Example 1

The same logic as Example 3.2 can be written more concisely using a lambda:

```java
textField.addActionListener(e -> {
    String input = textField.getText();
    label.setText("You entered: " + input);
});
```

The compiler treats this lambda as an implementation of `ActionListener` whose `actionPerformed` body is the lambda body. This single-line approach is **strongly recommended** in KTU 2024 Scheme answers for short handlers.

