## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 The Five-Step Operational Procedure for Implementing the Delegation Event Model

To successfully implement event handling in any Java GUI program, follow these **five mandatory steps**:

**Step 1 — Create the Event Source Component**
Instantiate a GUI component (e.g., `JButton`, `JTextField`) that will be capable of generating events. This component is added to a container such as a `JFrame` or `JPanel`.

```java
JButton submitButton = new JButton("Submit");
```

**Step 2 — Implement the Appropriate Listener Interface**
The listener is an object of a class that implements one (or more) of the event-listener interfaces defined in `java.awt.event` or `javax.swing.event`. Each interface declares one or more abstract methods (event handlers) that must be overridden.

```java
class MyListener implements ActionListener {
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // event-handling logic
    }
}
```

**Step 3 — Create the Listener Object**
Instantiate the listener class. This object will receive and process events from the source.

```java
MyListener listener = new MyListener();
```

**Step 4 — Register the Listener with the Event Source**
Call the source component's registration method (e.g., `addActionListener()`), passing the listener object as an argument. This **subscribes** the listener to the source.

```java
submitButton.addActionListener(listener);
```

**Step 5 — Event Generation and Delegation**
When the user interacts with the source (e.g., clicks the button), the source **automatically** creates an `EventObject` and invokes the appropriate callback method on **every registered listener**, passing the event object as an argument.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Board-Exam Insight:** In a 14-mark question, students frequently lose 2–3 marks for **forgetting to register the listener** (`addXxxListener()` call) or for **misspelling** the interface name (e.g., writing `ActionListerner` instead of `ActionListener`). Always double-check the spelling and registration step.

### 2.2 The Event Class Hierarchy (Delegation Model Foundation)

All event classes in the Delegation Event Model are subclasses of `java.util.EventObject` (a class in the standard utility package, *not* in AWT). This is a deliberate design choice that decouples the event-handling framework from AWT.

```
java.util.EventObject
        │
        └── java.awt.AWTEvent
                │
                ├── java.awt.event.ComponentEvent
                │       ├── java.awt.event.InputEvent
                │       │       ├── java.awt.event.KeyEvent
                │       │       └── java.awt.event.MouseEvent
                │       │              └── java.awt.event.MouseWheelEvent
                │       ├── java.awt.event.FocusEvent
                │       ├── java.awt.event.PaintEvent
                │       └── java.awt.event.WindowEvent
                │
                ├── java.awt.event.ActionEvent
                ├── java.awt.event.AdjustmentEvent
                ├── java.awt.event.ItemEvent
                └── java.awt.event.TextEvent
```

### 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet: Event-Listener Mapping Table

This is the **single most important table** for your KTU exam. Memorize the mapping between event types, source components, listener interfaces, and the registration method.

| **Event Class** | **Source Component** | **Listener Interface** | **Key Method(s) in Interface** | **Registration Method** |
|-----------------|----------------------|------------------------|--------------------------------|--------------------------|
| `ActionEvent` | `JButton`, `JMenuItem`, `JTextField` | `ActionListener` | `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` | `addActionListener()` |
| `MouseEvent` | Any `Component` | `MouseListener` | `mouseClicked`, `mousePressed`, `mouseReleased`, `mouseEntered`, `mouseExited` | `addMouseListener()` |
| `MouseEvent` (motion) | Any `Component` | `MouseMotionListener` | `mouseDragged`, `mouseMoved` | `addMouseMotionListener()` |
| `KeyEvent` | Any `Component` | `KeyListener` | `keyTyped`, `keyPressed`, `keyReleased` | `addKeyListener()` |
| `WindowEvent` | `JFrame`, `JDialog` | `WindowListener` | `windowOpened`, `windowClosing`, `windowClosed`, `windowActivated`, `windowDeactivated`, `windowIconified`, `windowDeiconified` | `addWindowListener()` |
| `ItemEvent` | `JCheckBox`, `JRadioButton`, `JComboBox` | `ItemListener` | `itemStateChanged(ItemEvent e)` | `addItemListener()` |
| `TextEvent` | `TextField`, `TextArea` | `TextListener` | `textValueChanged(TextEvent e)` | `addTextListener()` |
| `FocusEvent` | Any `Component` | `FocusListener` | `focusGained`, `focusLost` | `addFocusListener()` |

### 2.4 KTU Formula Sheet: Adapter Classes Reference

When a listener interface declares **many** abstract methods (e.g., `WindowListener` has 7 methods, `MouseListener` has 5), implementing the interface forces you to override *all* of them — even if you only need one. Java provides **Adapter classes** that provide **empty default implementations** of all methods, so you override only the ones you need.

| **Listener Interface** | **Adapter Class** | **Default Methods Provided (Empty)** |
|-----------------------|-------------------|--------------------------------------|
| `MouseListener` | `MouseAdapter` | All 5 mouse methods |
| `MouseMotionListener` | `MouseMotionAdapter` | Both motion methods |
| `KeyListener` | `KeyAdapter` | All 3 key methods |
| `WindowListener` | `WindowAdapter` | All 7 window methods |
| `FocusListener` | `FocusAdapter` | Both focus methods |

> [!NOTE]
> **Critical Note:** Adapters exist **only** for listener interfaces that have **more than one method**. Therefore, there is **no `ActionAdapter`** (because `ActionListener` has only one method, `actionPerformed`). Similarly, no `ItemAdapter` exists.

### 2.5 Engineering Utility & Real-World Application

The Delegation Event Model is the backbone of every interactive Java application:

- **Enterprise Desktop Applications:** NetBeans IDE, IntelliJ IDEA (Swing-based tools) rely on this model for menus, toolbars, and editor interactions.
- **Android Development:** Although Android uses a slightly different mechanism (`OnClickListener`, `setOnClickListener()`), the conceptual model is **directly derived** from Java's Delegation Event Model.
- **Web Frameworks:** JavaScript's addEventListener() and modern frontend frameworks (React, Vue) use the same *Observer* design pattern under the hood.
- **IoT & Robotics:** Java-based embedded GUIs for industrial control panels use DEM for touch and button interactions.

