## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

This section presents **exhaustive, line-by-line Java implementations** of the Delegation Event Model across the three most frequently examined event types in KTU: **ActionEvent**, **MouseEvent**, and **WindowEvent**. Every line of code is explained in detail to ensure full comprehension for board examination purposes.

### 3.1 Implementation 1: Handling an `ActionEvent` (Button Click)

This is the most fundamental and frequently tested scenario in KTU exams. The following program displays a button in a frame; when the user clicks the button, a message dialog appears.

```java
// File: ActionEventDemo.java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;

public class ActionEventDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    // Step 1: Declare the event source component as an instance variable
    private JButton clickButton;

    // Constructor: builds the GUI
    public ActionEventDemo() {
        // Set the title of the frame window
        setTitle("ActionEvent Demo - KTU");

        // Set the layout manager to FlowLayout (default for JFrame content pane)
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        // Step 1 (continued): Create the event source (a JButton)
        clickButton = new JButton("Click Me");

        // Step 4: Register the listener with the source
        // 'this' refers to the current ActionEventDemo object,
        // which implements ActionListener
        clickButton.addActionListener(this);

        // Add the button to the frame's content pane
        add(clickButton);

        // Configure the frame: size, default close operation, visibility
        setSize(300, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    // Step 2 & 3: Implement the ActionListener interface
    // Override the actionPerformed() callback method
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // 'e.getSource()' returns the component that generated the event
        if (e.getSource() == clickButton) {
            JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(this, 
                "Button was clicked! Event delegated successfully.",
                "KTU Demo", JOptionPane.INFORMATION_MESSAGE);
        }
    }

    // Main method: the entry point of the Java application
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Invoke the GUI constructor on the Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new ActionEventDemo());
    }
}
```

**Line-by-Line Logical Derivation:**

| Line / Block | Explanation | KTU Mark Weight |
|--------------|-------------|------------------|
| `class ActionEventDemo extends JFrame implements ActionListener` | The frame inherits from `JFrame` (to get a window) **and** implements `ActionListener` (so the same class can act as the listener). This is the "self-listening" pattern. | 2 marks |
| `private JButton clickButton;` | Declaring the button as a field (not a local variable) is **critical** because the `actionPerformed()` method must be able to reference it for comparison. | 1 mark |
| `setLayout(new FlowLayout());` | Without a layout manager, components may not appear at the expected positions. | 1 mark |
| `clickButton.addActionListener(this);` | **The most important line.** This is the actual *delegation registration*. Without this line, no event will ever reach the listener. | 3 marks |
| `public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)` | This is the **callback method**. It is automatically invoked by the AWT event-dispatch thread when the user clicks the button. | 3 marks |
| `SwingUtilities.invokeLater(...)` | Best practice in Swing: GUI creation must happen on the Event Dispatch Thread to avoid thread-safety issues. | 1 mark (extra credit) |

### 3.2 Implementation 2: Handling `MouseEvent` with an Anonymous Inner Class

This implementation demonstrates a **separate-class listener** (a non-self-listening pattern) using an **anonymous inner class** — a frequently tested KTU concept.

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;

public class MouseEventDemo extends JFrame {
    private JLabel statusLabel;

    public MouseEventDemo() {
        setTitle("MouseEvent Demo - KTU");
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        // A label to display mouse coordinates and event type
        statusLabel = new JLabel("Move the mouse over this area.");
        statusLabel.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(350, 50));

        // The label itself acts as the event source
        // We register a MouseListener using an anonymous inner class
        statusLabel.addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
            // Override only the methods we need
            public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {
                statusLabel.setText("Mouse Clicked at (" + e.getX() + ", " + e.getY() + ")");
            }

            public void mouseEntered(MouseEvent e) {
                statusLabel.setText("Mouse Entered the area.");
            }

            public void mouseExited(MouseEvent e) {
                statusLabel.setText("Mouse Exited the area.");
            }
        });

        add(statusLabel);
        setSize(400, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new MouseEventDemo());
    }
}
```

**Key Analytical Points:**

1. **`MouseAdapter` vs `MouseListener`:** Because `MouseListener` has 5 abstract methods, we use `MouseAdapter` (a class that provides empty implementations) to avoid writing empty bodies for `mousePressed` and `mouseReleased`.

2. **Anonymous Inner Class Syntax:** `new MouseAdapter() { ... }` creates an unnamed subclass of `MouseAdapter` inline at the point of use. This is concise and is the **preferred** KTU pattern when only one source component needs a unique listener.

3. **`MouseEvent` Methods Used:**
   - `e.getX()` and `e.getY()` → **integer** coordinates of the mouse pointer relative to the source component.
   - `e.getPoint()` → returns a `java.awt.Point` object containing both coordinates.
   - `e.getClickCount()` → number of consecutive clicks (useful for double-click detection).

### 3.3 Implementation 3: Handling `WindowEvent` Using a Lambda Expression (Modern Java)

Java 8+ allows listener interfaces with a **single abstract method (SAM)** to be implemented using **lambda expressions**. Although `WindowListener` has multiple methods (so lambdas cannot directly replace it), we can use `WindowAdapter` with a lambda-equivalent approach for specific methods — or, more practically, use the `addWindowListener` with a `WindowAdapter` and override only `windowClosing`.

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;

public class WindowEventDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> {
            JFrame frame = new JFrame("WindowEvent Demo - KTU");
            frame.setSize(400, 300);
            frame.setLayout(new FlowLayout());
            frame.add(new JLabel("Try closing this window."));

            // Register a WindowAdapter to handle window events
            frame.addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
                public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                    System.out.println("Window is closing. Releasing resources...");
                    // Perform cleanup, save data, etc.
                    System.exit(0);  // Terminate the application
                }

                public void windowOpened(WindowEvent e) {
                    System.out.println("Window opened successfully.");
                }
            });

            frame.setVisible(true);
        });
    }
}
```

### 3.4 Analytical Comparison Matrix: Three Listener Registration Styles

KTU 2024 Scheme examinations often include a **"compare and contrast"** question (typically worth 7 marks) on the three ways of registering a listener. This analytical matrix summarizes them.

| **Aspect** | **Self-Listening Class** | **Separate Listener Class** | **Anonymous Inner Class / Lambda** |
|------------|-------------------------|----------------------------|-------------------------------------|
| **Structure** | Main class `implements ActionListener` | Separate class `implements ActionListener` | Inline `new ActionListener() { ... }` or `e -> { ... }` |
| **Code Volume** | Smallest (single class) | Largest (two classes) | Medium (inline block) |
| **Readability** | Good for simple apps | Best for complex apps | Excellent for one-off listeners |
| **Reusability** | Listener logic tied to one class | Listener can be reused across multiple sources | Not reusable (defined inline) |
| **Access to GUI Fields** | Direct (no getters needed) | Requires `getter` methods or constructor parameters | Direct (captures enclosing class fields) |
| **When to Use** | Small programs, single button | Large apps, multiple sources share same logic | Most common in practice, GUI builders |

### 3.5 Critical Methods Available on `EventObject` (Parent of All Events)

All event classes inherit these methods from `java.util.EventObject`:

| Method | Return Type | Purpose |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `getSource()` | `Object` | Returns the object that generated the event (the event source) |
| `toString()` | `String` | Returns a human-readable string representation of the event |

> [!NOTE]
> **Board Tip:** When asked "How do you identify the source of an event in the listener?", the answer is: **"Call `e.getSource()` on the event object, which returns an `Object` reference to the originating component."** A common student error is to confuse `getSource()` (returns the *component*) with `getID()` (returns an *integer* event type identifier — e.g., `MouseEvent.MOUSE_CLICKED = 500`).

