#### **Question A (14 Marks)** — `[KTU University Exam – Dec 2024]`

**(a)** Explain the Delegation Event Model in Java. With a neat diagram, describe its components and the flow of event handling. (7 Marks)

**(b)** Write a Java program using Swing that creates a `JFrame` with a `JTextField` and a `JButton` labeled "Greet". When the button is clicked, the text entered in the `JTextField` should be displayed in a `JLabel` below as "Hello, [name]". (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**(a) Explanation (7 Marks):**

The Delegation Event Model is Java's standardized event-handling mechanism introduced in JDK 1.1 to replace the older inheritance-based model. In this architecture:

1. **Event Source:** A GUI component such as a `JButton`, `JTextField`, or `JFrame` that is capable of generating events. It exposes registration methods (e.g., `addActionListener()`) to which listener objects can subscribe.

2. **Event Object:** When the user interacts with the source (e.g., clicks the button), the source creates an event object — an instance of a subclass of `java.util.EventObject` (such as `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`, `KeyEvent`). This object carries all relevant information about the event (source, type, coordinates, modifiers, timestamp).

3. **Event Listener:** A listener is any object whose class implements one or more listener interfaces from `java.awt.event` or `javax.swing.event` (e.g., `ActionListener`). The interface declares callback methods (e.g., `actionPerformed(ActionEvent e)`) that the source invokes when an event occurs.

**Flow of Event Handling:**

$$\text{User Action} \rightarrow \text{Event Source} \rightarrow \text{Event Object Created} \rightarrow \text{EDT Dispatches Event} \rightarrow \text{Callback Method Invoked on Listener} \rightarrow \text{Event Handled}$$

The flow diagram (see Section 4.1) summarizes this process. The source and listener are **loosely coupled** — the source does not know the concrete class of the listener, only that it implements the required interface. This follows the **Observer Design Pattern**.

**Key advantages:** (i) Clean separation of concerns, (ii) A single source can have multiple listeners, (iii) A single listener can handle events from multiple sources, (iv) Easy to add or remove listeners dynamically.

**(b) Java Program (7 Marks):**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;

public class GreetApp extends JFrame implements ActionListener {
    private JTextField nameField;
    private JLabel greetLabel;
    private JButton greetButton;

    public GreetApp() {
        setTitle("Greet App - KTU 2024");
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        add(new JLabel("Enter your name: "));
        nameField = new JTextField(15);
        add(nameField);

        greetButton = new JButton("Greet");
        add(greetButton);

        greetLabel = new JLabel(" ");
        add(greetLabel);

        // Register the listener
        greetButton.addActionListener(this);

        setSize(350, 150);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        String name = nameField.getText();
        greetLabel.setText("Hello, " + name + " !");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new GreetApp());
    }
}
```

