#### **Question B (14 Marks)** — `[KTU University Exam – May 2023]`

**(a)** Differentiate between the **Inheritance-based Event Model** and the **Delegation Event Model** in Java. List any four advantages of the Delegation Event Model. (7 Marks)

**(b)** Write a complete Java Swing program to demonstrate `MouseListener`. The program should display a `JFrame` containing a `JPanel`, and when the user clicks the mouse on the panel, the click coordinates `(x, y)` and the click count should be displayed in a `JLabel`. (7 Marks)

**Model Solution:**

**(a) Comparison (7 Marks):**

| **Aspect** | **Inheritance-Based Model (Pre-JDK 1.1)** | **Delegation Event Model (JDK 1.1+)** |
|------------|------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------|
| **Mechanism** | Subclass the component class and override event-handling methods like `action()`, `handleEvent()` | Implement a listener interface and register it with the source |
| **Coupling** | Tight coupling: every component must extend `java.awt.Component` to handle events | Loose coupling: any class can be a listener by implementing an interface |
| **Multiple Handlers** | Difficult; requires complex method dispatch | Easy: a source can have multiple listeners, all notified of the same event |
| **Extensibility** | Limited; adding new event types requires changes to the class hierarchy | Extensible; new event types can be added without modifying existing code |
| **Method Overriding** | Must override `handleEvent()` and manually switch on event IDs | Override only the specific callback method (e.g., `actionPerformed()`) |
| **JavaBeans Compatibility** | Not compatible with JavaBeans event model | Fully compatible — the foundation of the JavaBeans specification |

**Four Advantages of the Delegation Event Model:**

1. **Clean separation of concerns:** The GUI component focuses on rendering, while the listener focuses on behavior.
2. **Multiple listeners per source:** Many listener objects can subscribe to the same source component.
3. **Reusability of listeners:** A single listener object can be registered with multiple sources.
4. **Dynamic registration:** Listeners can be added or removed at runtime using `addXxxListener()` and `removeXxxListener()`.

**(b) Java Program with `MouseListener` (7 Marks):**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;
import javax.swing.*;

public class MouseClickPanel extends JFrame {
    private JLabel coordLabel;
    private JPanel drawingPanel;

    public MouseClickPanel() {
        setTitle("Mouse Click Demo - KTU 2023");
        setLayout(new BorderLayout());

        // Status label at the top
        coordLabel = new JLabel("Click anywhere on the panel below.");
        add(coordLabel, BorderLayout.NORTH);

        // Panel where clicks are detected
        drawingPanel = new JPanel();
        drawingPanel.setBackground(Color.LIGHT_GRAY);
        add(drawingPanel, BorderLayout.CENTER);

        // Register a MouseAdapter (overriding only mouseClicked)
        drawingPanel.addMouseListener(new MouseAdapter() {
            public void mouseClicked(MouseEvent e) {
                int x = e.getX();
                int y = e.getY();
                int clicks = e.getClickCount();
                coordLabel.setText("Clicked at (" + x + ", " + y + 
                                   ") | Click Count: " + clicks);
            }
        });

        setSize(400, 300);
        setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
        setVisible(true);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SwingUtilities.invokeLater(() -> new MouseClickPanel());
    }
}
```

