> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning — Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting `addXxxListener()` call (–2 to –3 marks):** The most common error. The listener class may be perfectly written, but without registration, the event will never reach it. Always check this line in your code review.
> 2. **Misspelling interface names (–1 mark each):** `ActionListerner`, `MouseListner` — board examiners deduct marks for every such typo. Spelling counts.
> 3. **Implementing the listener interface but not overriding the required method (–2 marks):** For example, writing `class X implements ActionListener` without overriding `actionPerformed()`. The code will not compile.
> 4. **Confusing `getSource()` with `getID()` (–1 mark):** `getSource()` returns the *component* (an `Object`), while `getID()` returns an *integer* event-type identifier. These are fundamentally different.
> 5. **Using `frame.setVisible(true)` *before* `addXxxListener()` (–1 mark):** Although it does not cause a compile error, it is considered poor practice because any events fired during the brief construction window will be lost. Register listeners first, then make the frame visible.
> 6. **Forgetting `setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE)` (–1 mark):** Without this, clicking the window's close button will hide the frame but **not terminate the JVM**, causing the program to continue running silently in the background.

