# Module 4 — Event Classes

> [!NOTE]
> **Syllabus Highlight (KTU 2024 Scheme, PECIT633):** This topic falls under the **Delegation Event Model** unit of Module 4. Students must master the **class hierarchy**, **constructors**, and **key accessor methods** of event classes in `java.awt.event` and `javax.swing.event`. Event classes are the *payload carriers* of Java's event-handling architecture.

## 1.1 Formal Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Definition (KTU Board Standard):**
> An **Event Class** in Java is a class that encapsulates the information describing a *specific occurrence* in the lifetime of a graphical user interface (GUI) — typically a user interaction (mouse click, key press, button activation) or a system notification (window opening, focus change). Every event class in AWT/Swing is a subclass of `java.util.EventObject`, which guarantees the presence of a **source** object and a **persistent** event representation that can be passed across threads and listeners.

Formally, an event object must satisfy three contracts:

1. **Identity of the source** — accessible via `EventObject.getSource()`.
2. **Type / semantic of the occurrence** — represented by the concrete subclass (e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`) and the event **ID** (an `int` constant such as `MOUSE_CLICKED = 500`).
3. **Immutability of identity fields** — once constructed, the source reference is final; the event is *frozen* and safely propagated.

All concrete event classes used by AWT listeners reside in the package **`java.awt.event`**, and all swing-specific extensions reside in **`javax.swing.event`**.

## 1.2 Intuitive Analogy — The "Incident Report"

Imagine a **hospital emergency room**. Every time a patient arrives, the *triage nurse* fills out an **Incident Report Form** that contains:

- *Who* brought the patient in (the **source**).
- *What kind* of emergency it is — heart attack, fracture, fever (the **event type / class**).
- *Specific details* — heart rate, blood pressure, time of arrival (the **event-specific data**, e.g., `x`, `y`, `keyChar`).

That form is then handed over to the **specialist doctor** (the **listener / handler**) who decides what to do.

In Java, the *triage nurse* is the **AWT event dispatching thread**, the *form* is the **Event Class instance**, and the *doctor* is the **Listener interface implementation**. Event classes are simply the **standardized, immutable envelopes** that carry every fact the listener needs to react intelligently.

> [!TIP]
> **Memory Hook:** *Event Class = Sealed Envelope.* The envelope is sealed at creation; the *source* is the return address printed on it; the *stamp* on the envelope is the **event ID**; the *contents* are the event-specific data fields (coordinates, key codes, etc.).

## 1.3 Why Event Classes Exist — The Engineering Rationale

A naïve GUI design would have the button subclass *know* what to do on click — leading to **tight coupling** and the un-maintainable "control-flow inversion" of early toolkits. Java's **Delegation Event Model** solves this by:

1. **Decoupling** — the source component (`JButton`, `JTextField`) does *not* know *who* will handle its events. It only knows that *something* is registered as a listener.
2. **Standardisation** — every event type has a single, well-documented class so the listener always knows the exact shape of the data it receives.
3. **Multicast delivery** — one event object can be dispatched to *many* listeners in the listener list.

Event classes are therefore the **lingua franca** (common language) between GUI components and application logic.
