# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis — The Event-Class Architecture

## 2.1 The Class Hierarchy (Inheritance Chain)

The entire AWT event family descends from a **two-level chain**:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\texttt{java.util.EventObject} \quad &\longrightarrow \quad \texttt{java.awt.AWTEvent} \\[2pt]
&\longrightarrow \quad \text{Concrete event classes in } \texttt{java.awt.event}
\end{aligned}
$$

- **`java.util.EventObject`** — the *abstract root*. Provides `getSource()` and the contract that every event has a source. It is *not* AWT-specific.
- **`java.awt.AWTEvent`** — adds the **event ID** mechanism (`getID()`) and the `consume()` mechanism used by AWT for event *consumption* (allowing low-level listeners to swallow events before higher-level ones see them).
- **Concrete event classes** — e.g., `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`, `KeyEvent`, `WindowEvent`, `ItemEvent`, `TextEvent`, `FocusEvent`, `AdjustmentEvent`, `ComponentEvent`, `ContainerEvent`, `InputEvent`, `PaintEvent`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`InputEvent`** is itself an abstract subclass of `AWTEvent` and the **direct superclass** of both `KeyEvent` and `MouseEvent`. This is why modifier-key flags (Shift, Ctrl, Alt, Meta) are defined once on `InputEvent` and inherited by both subclasses.

## 2.2 Operational Walk-Through — Life of an Event Object

The following bulleted sequence describes exactly *how* an event class instance is born, transported, and consumed in a KTU-typical AWT program.

1. **User Action Occurs** — a user clicks the mouse, presses a key, or activates a button. The underlying operating system (or the Java Robot / synthetic event API) reports the action to the JVM.
2. **Source Component Receives a `processEvent` Call** — every `java.awt.Component` has a `processEvent(AWTEvent e)` method. Subclasses like `Button`, `TextField`, etc., override this to dispatch to specialized `process<Action>Event` methods.
3. **Event Object Construction** — the `processXxxEvent` method constructs the *appropriate* event class instance. For example, when a button is clicked, the AWT machinery calls:

   ```java
   new ActionEvent(this, ActionEvent.ACTION_PERFORMED, command);
   ```

4. **Dispatch via `EventQueue`** — the freshly minted event object is enqueued onto the **system event queue** (`java.awt.EventQueue`) and later pumped onto the **AWT Event Dispatch Thread (EDT)**.
5. **Listener Notification** — the component's `EventListener` registry is iterated. For every registered listener that *matches* the event class, the appropriate callback (`actionPerformed`, `mouseClicked`, `keyPressed`, etc.) is invoked with the event object as its single argument.
6. **Listener Inspects Event Data** — the listener calls accessor methods (`e.getX()`, `e.getKeyChar()`, `e.getItem()`, etc.) to extract event-specific information and decide on a response.
7. **Garbage Collection** — once all listeners have returned and the event is no longer referenced, it becomes eligible for GC. **Events are short-lived, single-use objects.**

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet — The Major Event Classes

> [!NOTE]
> The table below is the **canonical reference** KTU examiners expect you to memorise. It covers every concrete event class typically tested in PECIT633, its package, its key constructors (signature), and its most-frequently-tested accessor methods.

| **Event Class** | **Source Components** | **Constructor Signature** | **Key Accessor Methods** | **Listener Interface** |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| `ActionEvent` | `Button`, `JButton`, `JTextField` (on Enter), `List`, `MenuItem` | `ActionEvent(Object src, int id, String cmd)` | `getActionCommand()`, `getModifiers()` | `ActionListener` |
| `ItemEvent` | `Checkbox`, `CheckboxMenuItem`, `Choice`, `List` | `ItemEvent(ItemSelectable src, int id, Object item, int stateChange)` | `getItem()`, `getItemSelectable()`, `getStateChange()` | `ItemListener` |
| `KeyEvent` | Any `Component` gaining focus | `KeyEvent(Component src, int id, long when, int mods, int keyCode, char keyChar)` | `getKeyChar()`, `getKeyCode()`, `getKeyText(int)`, `getModifiersEx()` | `KeyListener` |
| `MouseEvent` | Any `Component` under the mouse | `MouseEvent(Component src, int id, long when, int mods, int x, int y, int clickCount, boolean popupTrigger, int button)` | `getX()`, `getY()`, `getPoint()`, `getClickCount()`, `getButton()`, `isPopupTrigger()` | `MouseListener`, `MouseMotionListener` |
| `MouseWheelEvent` | Any `Component` under a scrolling wheel | `MouseWheelEvent(Component src, int id, long when, int mods, int x, int y, int clickCount, boolean popupTrigger, int wheelRotation, double preciseWheelRotation)` | `getWheelRotation()`, `getPreciseWheelRotation()`, `getScrollType()` | `MouseWheelListener` |
| `WindowEvent` | `Window`, `JWindow`, `JFrame`, `JDialog` | `WindowEvent(Window src, int id, Window opposite, int oldState, int newState)` | `getWindow()`, `getOppositeWindow()`, `getNewState()` | `WindowListener`, `WindowStateListener` |
| `FocusEvent` | Any focus-traversable `Component` | `FocusEvent(Component src, int id, boolean temporary, Component opposite)` | `isTemporary()`, `getOppositeComponent()` | `FocusListener` |
| `ComponentEvent` | Any `Component` (moved, resized, shown, hidden) | `ComponentEvent(Component src, int id)` | `getComponent()` | `ComponentListener` |
| `ContainerEvent` | Any `Container` (child added/removed) | `ContainerEvent(Component src, int id, Component child)` | `getChild()`, `getContainer()` | `ContainerListener` |
| `AdjustmentEvent` | `Scrollbar`, `JScrollBar` (via `Adjustable`) | `AdjustmentEvent(Adjustable src, int id, int type, int value)` | `getAdjustable()`, `getAdjustmentType()`, `getValue()` | `AdjustmentListener` |
| `TextEvent` | `TextField`, `TextArea`, `JTextComponent` | `TextEvent(Object src, int id)` | *(inherits only `getSource()`)* | `TextListener` |
| `PaintEvent` | Any `Component` requiring repaint (system-internal) | `PaintEvent(Component src, int id, Rectangle updateRect)` | `getUpdateRect()` | *(no public listener; handled by system)* |
| `InputEvent` *(abstract)* | — | — | `isShiftDown()`, `isControlDown()`, `isAltDown()`, `isMetaDown()`, `getModifiersEx()` | *(parent of `KeyEvent` and `MouseEvent`)* |

> [!TIP]
> **`InputEvent` modifier flags** are tested frequently. The constants are `SHIFT_MASK = 1`, `CTRL_MASK = 2`, `META_MASK = 4`, `ALT_MASK = 8`. Combined modifiers use bitwise OR, e.g., `SHIFT_MASK \vert ALT_MASK`.

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

Event classes are the **substrate** of every interactive Java application — from banking terminals (every key press is a `KeyEvent`) to flight-management GUIs (a `WindowEvent` fires when a control-tower window loses focus). They are also the foundation of **test automation frameworks** (Selenium, AssertJ-Swing) which *synthesise* event objects and dispatch them into the queue to drive the UI without real user input. Modern frameworks like **RxJava** even extend the event-class pattern to *asynchronous streams* of `OnNext`, `OnError`, `OnComplete` notifications, demonstrating that the Java event-class design has scaled far beyond the GUI domain.
