# 3. Step-by-Step Analytical Walk-Through

## 3.1 Deriving the Event-Class Inheritance Tree

The hierarchy is not arbitrary — each level of inheritance adds a **specific category of behaviour**. We walk downward:

$$
\begin{aligned}
&\textbf{Level 0: } \texttt{java.util.EventObject} \\
&\quad \Rightarrow \text{adds } \texttt{getSource()} \text{ — every event must report its originator.} \\[4pt]
&\textbf{Level 1: } \texttt{java.awt.AWTEvent} \;\text{(extends EventObject)} \\
&\quad \Rightarrow \text{adds the } \textbf{id} \text{ field and } \texttt{getID()}. \\
&\quad \Rightarrow \text{adds the } \texttt{consumed} \text{ flag and } \texttt{consume() / isConsumed()}. \\
&\quad \Rightarrow \text{provides the } \texttt{reserved}-id \text{ ranges used by AWT (starting at 500).} \\[4pt]
&\textbf{Level 2: Concrete classes} \\
&\quad \Rightarrow \text{add } \textbf{type-specific payload} \text{ (x, y, keyCode, keyChar, ...).}
\end{aligned}
$$

The crucial insight is that `InputEvent` is an **intermediate abstract node** that consolidates *keyboard* and *mouse* events under a common parent because they both carry **modifier flags** (Shift, Ctrl, Alt, Meta). Without `InputEvent`, modifier logic would have to be duplicated in `KeyEvent` and `MouseEvent`.

The structural derivation can be expressed as:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\texttt{EventObject} &\longrightarrow \texttt{AWTEvent} \\
\texttt{AWTEvent} &\longrightarrow \begin{cases} \texttt{InputEvent (abstract)} \longrightarrow \begin{cases} \texttt{KeyEvent} \\ \texttt{MouseEvent} \longrightarrow \texttt{MouseWheelEvent} \end{cases} \\[4pt] \texttt{ComponentEvent} \longrightarrow \begin{cases} \texttt{ContainerEvent} \\ \texttt{FocusEvent} \\ \texttt{WindowEvent} \\ \texttt{PaintEvent} \end{cases} \\[4pt] \texttt{ActionEvent} \\ \texttt{ItemEvent} \\ \texttt{AdjustmentEvent} \\ \texttt{TextEvent} \end{cases}
\end{aligned}
$$

## 3.2 Exhaustive Worked Example — A Multi-Event Demonstration Program

The following program is a **complete, compilable** KTU-style AWT applet-style Java program (rewritten here as a top-level class for clarity) that demonstrates **three** different event classes — `ActionEvent`, `KeyEvent`, and `WindowEvent` — in a single runnable file. Every relevant method call is annotated.

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class EventClassDemo extends Frame
        implements ActionListener, KeyListener, WindowListener {

    private TextField tfInput;
    private TextArea  taLog;
    private Button    btnClear;

    public EventClassDemo() {
        // --- Step 1: Construct the GUI components ---
        setTitle("KTU Event Class Demonstration");
        setSize(500, 320);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        tfInput = new TextField(20);
        taLog   = new TextArea(12, 60);
        btnClear = new Button("Clear Log");

        add(new Label("Type something and press Enter:"));
        add(tfInput);
        add(btnClear);
        add(taLog);

        // --- Step 2: Register listeners (this is the Delegation Event Model) ---
        tfInput.addActionListener(this);   // produces ActionEvent
        tfInput.addKeyListener(this);      // produces KeyEvent
        btnClear.addActionListener(this);  // also produces ActionEvent
        addWindowListener(this);           // produces WindowEvent

        setVisible(true);
    }

    // ===== ActionEvent handling (ActionListener) =====
    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // getSource() — inherited from java.util.EventObject
        Object src = e.getSource();

        // getActionCommand() — defined on ActionEvent itself
        String cmd = e.getActionCommand();

        // getID() — inherited from AWTEvent; for ActionEvent id = ACTION_PERFORMED
        int id = e.getID();

        taLog.append("[ActionEvent]  source=" + src.getClass().getSimpleName()
                     + "  command=\"" + cmd + "\"  id=" + id + "\n");

        if (e.getSource() == btnClear) {
            taLog.setText("");
        }
    }

    // ===== KeyEvent handling (KeyListener) =====
    @Override
    public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) {
        // getKeyChar() — defined on KeyEvent
        char c = e.getKeyChar();
        taLog.append("[KeyEvent]    keyTyped   char='" + c
                     + "' (int " + (int) c + ")\n");
    }

    @Override
    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
        // getKeyCode() — virtual key code; getKeyText returns a human label
        int code = e.getKeyCode();
        taLog.append("[KeyEvent]    keyPressed code=" + code
                     + " (" + KeyEvent.getKeyText(code) + ")\n");
    }

    @Override
    public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e) {
        taLog.append("[KeyEvent]    keyReleased code="
                     + e.getKeyCode() + "\n");
    }

    // ===== WindowEvent handling (WindowListener) =====
    @Override public void windowOpened(WindowEvent e)  {
        taLog.append("[WindowEvent] WINDOW_OPENED on "
                     + e.getWindow().getName() + "\n");
    }
    @Override public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
        taLog.append("[WindowEvent] WINDOW_CLOSING — exiting\n");
        e.getWindow().dispose();
        System.exit(0);
    }
    @Override public void windowClosed(WindowEvent e)   { /* no-op */ }
    @Override public void windowIconified(WindowEvent e){ /* no-op */ }
    @Override public void windowDeiconified(WindowEvent e){ /* no-op */ }
    @Override public void windowActivated(WindowEvent e){ /* no-op */ }
    @Override public void windowDeactivated(WindowEvent e){ /* no-op */ }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new EventClassDemo();
    }
}
```

### Step-by-Step Analysis of the Program

1. **Event Class Selection** — the GUI uses *four* sources, each producing a *different* event class:
   - `TextField` typing → `KeyEvent`
   - `TextField` Enter key or `Button` click → `ActionEvent`
   - Frame open/close → `WindowEvent`

2. **Listener Registration** — `addActionListener`, `addKeyListener`, `addWindowListener` are calls on the source. They store the listener in the source's internal `EventListener` vector.

3. **ActionEvent inspection** — the `actionPerformed` method calls `e.getSource()` (inherited from `EventObject`), `e.getActionCommand()` (defined on `ActionEvent`), and `e.getID()` (inherited from `AWTEvent`). This pattern is the textbook KTU answer for *“explain how the listener extracts data from an event object”*.

4. **KeyEvent inspection** — note that `getKeyChar()` returns the *character produced* (respecting Shift / Caps-Lock), whereas `getKeyCode()` returns the *physical key location* (e.g., `VK_A` regardless of shift). The static `KeyEvent.getKeyText(int)` converts a code to a string like `"A"` or `"F1"`.

5. **WindowEvent inspection** — `e.getWindow()` returns the `Window` object that fired the event, allowing the listener to call `dispose()` on it.

> [!TIP]
> **Why the empty methods in `WindowListener`?** Java pre-Java-8 required *all* interface methods to be implemented explicitly. The seven `no-op` methods are a KTU-recognised idiom. Modern code (Java 8+) replaces them with `addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() { ... })`, where `WindowAdapter` is a no-op *adapter class*.

