## 5.1 Part A — Short-Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### Q1. `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`
**List any three concrete event classes from the `java.awt.event` package and state one accessor method unique to each.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

1. **`ActionEvent`** — accessor `getActionCommand()`: returns the command string associated with the action (e.g., the button label, or the text of a `TextField` after Enter). **1 mark**
2. **`MouseEvent`** — accessor `getX()` (and `getY()`): returns the integer x-coordinate (and y-coordinate) of the mouse pointer at the time the event occurred, relative to the source component. **1 mark**
3. **`KeyEvent`** — accessor `getKeyChar()`: returns the *character* produced by the key event, taking into account Shift, Caps-Lock, and the OS keyboard layout. **1 mark**

### Q2. `[KTU University Exam — June 2024]`
**What is the role of `java.util.EventObject`? Why is it the superclass of all AWT event classes?**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**
- `java.util.EventObject` is the **abstract root** of the entire Java event-class hierarchy. It defines the contract that every event must carry a **source** — the object that originated the event. **1 mark**
- It provides the inherited method `Object getSource()` which every listener can rely upon, regardless of the concrete event type. **1 mark**
- Because it is the universal superclass, listeners can write *generic* event-handling code (e.g., a single `Logger` that handles every event class polymorphically). It also lets non-AWT frameworks (Spring, JavaBeans) reuse the same root for their own event systems. **1 mark**

