## 5.2 Part B — Long-Answer Questions (14 Marks Each, Internal Choice)

> [!NOTE]
> KTU 2024 Scheme Part B questions on this module typically expect *one* full Java program plus conceptual exposition. Marks are split **7 + 7** between the two sub-parts (a) and (b). Use clear headings and comments in code for valuation clarity.

### Question A (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam — May 2024]`

**(a)** With a neat inheritance diagram, explain the hierarchy of event classes in `java.awt.event`. List at least **five** concrete event classes and the component that generates each. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a complete Java AWT program that creates a `Frame` containing a `TextField`, a `Label`, and a `Button` labeled "Show". When the user types in the `TextField` and presses **Enter**, the typed text should appear in the `Label`. When the **Show** button is clicked, the same text should also appear in the `Label`. Use the appropriate event classes and listener interfaces. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Question A

**(a) Event-class hierarchy (7 marks)**

The hierarchy descends from `java.util.EventObject`, with `java.awt.AWTEvent` as the first AWT-specific ancestor:

- `EventObject` → `AWTEvent` → concrete event classes.

Five concrete event classes and their source components:

| **Event Class** | **Source Component(s)** | **Generated When** |
|---|---|---|
| `ActionEvent` | `Button`, `TextField` (on Enter), `MenuItem`, `List` | Button clicked, Enter pressed, menu item chosen |
| `MouseEvent` | Any `Component` under the mouse pointer | Mouse pressed, released, clicked, entered, exited |
| `KeyEvent` | The `Component` that currently has focus | Key pressed, released, or typed |
| `WindowEvent` | `Window`, `Frame`, `Dialog` | Window opened, closing, closed, iconified, etc. |
| `ItemEvent` | `Checkbox`, `Choice`, `List` | Item selection or deselection |

**Mark split:** 2 marks for the hierarchy text, 3 marks for the diagram (5 concrete classes × 0.6 = 3), 2 marks for the source-component mapping.

**(b) Java AWT program (7 marks)**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class EnterEcho extends Frame implements ActionListener {
    private TextField tf;
    private Label lbl;
    private Button btn;

    public EnterEcho() {
        setTitle("Enter Echo Demo");
        setSize(400, 150);
        setLayout(new FlowLayout());

        tf  = new TextField(20);
        lbl = new Label("Output appears here");
        btn = new Button("Show");

        add(tf);
        add(btn);
        add(lbl);

        // Registering listeners — Delegation Event Model
        tf.addActionListener(this);   // ActionEvent from Enter
        btn.addActionListener(this);  // ActionEvent from click

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                dispose();
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        // Use the ActionEvent object's payload
        String text = tf.getText();
        lbl.setText("Echo: " + text);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new EnterEcho();
    }
}
```

**Mark split:** 2 marks for class structure & GUI construction, 2 marks for listener registration, 2 marks for `actionPerformed` logic, 1 mark for the window-closing handler.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout:**
> 1. **Forgetting to register the listener** — students often write `implements ActionListener` but forget `tf.addActionListener(this)`. Without registration, **no event will ever arrive** and the program silently does nothing. **−2 marks** typical deduction.
> 2. **Reading text from the `ActionEvent` rather than the `TextField`** — a common mistake is `e.getActionCommand()` on a button click, which returns the button label, not the text-field contents. Use `tf.getText()` for the actual input. **−1 mark** if confused.
> 3. **Missing the window-closing handler** — the JVM will hang at termination if `windowClosing` is not implemented. **−1 mark** for the program not exiting cleanly.

---

### Question B (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]`

**(a)** Differentiate between `getKeyChar()` and `getKeyCode()` in `KeyEvent`. Explain when each method is appropriate to use, with a small code snippet for each. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a Java AWT program that uses **two different event classes** — `KeyEvent` and `MouseEvent` — on the same `Frame`. The program should: (i) display the coordinates of the mouse in a `Label` whenever the mouse is moved over the frame, and (ii) display the typed key character in a different `Label` whenever a key is pressed while the frame has focus. **(7 marks)**

---

#### Model Solution — Question B

**(a) `getKeyChar()` vs `getKeyCode()` (7 marks)**

| **Aspect** | `getKeyChar()` | `getKeyCode()` |
|---|---|---|
| **Return type** | `char` | `int` |
| **Meaning** | The *character produced* by the key event (e.g., `'A'` for Shift + `A`, `'a'` for plain `A`) | The *virtual key code* identifying the *physical key* (e.g., `VK_A` regardless of Shift) |
| **Source definition** | Defined on `KeyEvent` itself | Defined on `KeyEvent` (constants from `KeyEvent` such as `VK_F1`, `VK_ENTER`) |
| **Appropriate when** | The application cares about the *textual content* typed — e.g., a text editor, search field, password box | The application cares about *which physical key* was struck — e.g., function-key shortcuts (F1 = Help), arrow-key navigation, game controls |
| **Key release** | Returns `KEY_CHAR_UNDEFINED` (a sentinel) for `KEY_RELEASED` events because no character is produced on release | Returns a valid code on both `KEY_PRESSED` and `KEY_RELEASED` |

Code snippet for `getKeyChar()` — appending to a `TextArea`:

```java
public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e) {
    textArea.append(String.valueOf(e.getKeyChar()));
}
```

Code snippet for `getKeyCode()` — handling function keys:

```java
public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
    if (e.getKeyCode() == KeyEvent.VK_F1) {
        showHelpDialog();
    } else if (e.getKeyCode() == KeyEvent.VK_ESCAPE) {
        System.exit(0);
    }
}
```

**Mark split:** 2 marks for the comparison table, 2 marks for the "when to use" distinction, 3 marks for the two code snippets.

**(b) Multi-event Java program (7 marks)**

```java
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.event.*;

public class MultiEventDemo extends Frame
        implements MouseMotionListener, KeyListener {

    private Label lblMouse, lblKey;

    public MultiEventDemo() {
        setTitle("Mouse and Key Event Demo");
        setSize(450, 150);
        setLayout(new GridLayout(3, 1));
        setBackground(Color.lightGray);

        lblMouse = new Label("Mouse position: (0, 0)");
        lblKey   = new Label("Last key: (none)");
        Label title = new Label("Move the mouse and press keys.");

        add(title);
        add(lblMouse);
        add(lblKey);

        // Register listeners — two different event classes
        addMouseMotionListener(this);   // produces MouseEvent (mouse moved/dragged)
        addKeyListener(this);           // produces KeyEvent (keys)

        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent e) {
                dispose();
                System.exit(0);
            }
        });

        setVisible(true);
        // Ensure the frame, not a child, has focus to receive keys
        setFocusable(true);
        requestFocus();
    }

    // MouseMotionListener — receives MouseEvent on movement
    @Override
    public void mouseMoved(MouseEvent e) {
        lblMouse.setText("Mouse position: ("
                         + e.getX() + ", " + e.getY() + ")");
    }

    @Override
    public void mouseDragged(MouseEvent e) { /* unused */ }

    // KeyListener — receives KeyEvent
    @Override
    public void keyPressed(KeyEvent e) {
        lblKey.setText("Last key pressed: code="
                       + e.getKeyCode() + "  char='"
                       + e.getKeyChar() + "'  text=\""
                       + KeyEvent.getKeyText(e.getKeyCode()) + "\"");
    }

    @Override public void keyTyped(KeyEvent e)    { /* unused */ }
    @Override public void keyReleased(KeyEvent e) { /* unused */ }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new MultiEventDemo();
    }
}
```

**Mark split:** 1 mark for class declaration & interface implementation, 2 marks for listener registration (both `addMouseMotionListener` and `addKeyListener`), 2 marks for the `mouseMoved` and `keyPressed` methods using the right event-class accessors, 1 mark for focus & window-closing handling, 1 mark for compilation-readiness.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout:**
> 1. **Using `MouseListener` instead of `MouseMotionListener`** — `MouseListener` only fires for click/enter/exit events, *not* for movement. To track mouse position, you **must** use `MouseMotionListener.mouseMoved`. **−2 marks** for the wrong interface.
> 2. **Forgetting `requestFocus()` on the `Frame`** — `KeyEvent`s are delivered to the focus owner. If focus is on a child component, the frame's `keyPressed` will not fire. **−1 mark** for non-working keyboard input.
> 3. **Implementing `MouseListener` *and* `MouseMotionListener` separately** when both are needed — you can `implements MouseListener, MouseMotionListener` on the same class, since Java supports multiple interface implementation. **−1 mark** if the student creates two handler classes unnecessarily.

