## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!TIP]
> **Rapid-Revision Checklist — Event Classes**

- **Root of the hierarchy:** `java.util.EventObject` → `java.awt.AWTEvent` → concrete event classes.
- **Every event object exposes `getSource()`** (inherited from `EventObject`).
- **Every AWT event exposes `getID()`** (inherited from `AWTEvent`), returning an `int` constant that distinguishes subtypes within the same class.
- **Five event classes you absolutely must know:** `ActionEvent`, `MouseEvent`, `KeyEvent`, `WindowEvent`, `ItemEvent`.
- **Two key accessors of `KeyEvent`:** `getKeyChar()` (the *character* produced) and `getKeyCode()` (the *physical key* code, e.g., `VK_F1`).
- **`MouseEvent` provides coordinates** via `getX()`, `getY()`, or `getPoint()`. `getClickCount()` distinguishes single from double clicks.
- **`ActionEvent.getActionCommand()`** returns the command string — the button label, the text-field content on Enter, or the menu-item label.
- **`WindowEvent.getWindow()`** returns the source `Window` object, useful for `dispose()` calls.
- **`InputEvent` is abstract** and the parent of both `KeyEvent` and `MouseEvent`, sharing modifier-key flags (`isShiftDown()`, `isControlDown()`, etc.).
- **Event objects are short-lived, single-use, and immutable**; they are not retained by the AWT machinery after dispatch.
- **Listeners are paired with event classes by the JDK API** — `ActionListener ↔ ActionEvent`, `KeyListener ↔ KeyEvent`, `WindowListener ↔ WindowEvent`, etc. Memorise the pairing.
- **Adapter classes** (`WindowAdapter`, `KeyAdapter`, `MouseAdapter`, `FocusAdapter`, etc.) provide empty implementations of listener interfaces so you override only the methods you need — preferred over 7-line no-op shells.
- **Constructor signature pattern** for most event classes: `(Component src, int id, ... type-specific fields ...)`.
- **Reserved event-ID range:** AWT event IDs start at **500** (e.g., `ACTION_EVENT = 1001`, `MOUSE_FIRST = 500`, `MOUSE_LAST = 506`); user-defined IDs should be > `AWTEvent.RESERVED_ID_MAX = 1999` to avoid clashes.
- **Common bug:** registering the wrong listener interface (`MouseListener` for movement) — always verify against the API.
- **EDT safety:** event-handling methods are invoked on the **AWT Event Dispatch Thread**; long-running tasks inside listeners will freeze the GUI.
