# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

## 2.1 The 5-Step CRUD Workflow (The "JDBC Lifecycle")

Every JDBC interaction — whether Create, Read, Update, or Delete — follows this universal **5-step lifecycle**. Mastering this sequence guarantees full marks on any JDBC question in the KTU exam.

### Step 1: Load and Register the Driver
The driver class must be loaded into memory so the `DriverManager` knows which vendor-specific implementation to use.

```java
// Modern approach (Java SE 6+ uses SPI, manual loading is optional)
Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");
```

The `forName()` method triggers the driver's static initializer, which automatically registers itself with `DriverManager` via the **JDBC 4.0+ Service Provider mechanism** (the file `META-INF/services/java.sql.Driver` inside the driver JAR).

### Step 2: Establish the Connection
The connection is created using a **JDBC URL** (Uniform Resource Locator) that uniquely identifies the database.

```java
Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(
    "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/studentdb",  // JDBC URL
    "root",                                    // username
    "password"                                 // password
);
```

**JDBC URL Anatomy:**

```
jdbc:<subprotocol>:<subname>
  |        |            |
  |        |            └── Database name / parameters
  |        └── Vendor name (mysql, oracle, postgresql, etc.)
  └── Protocol identifier (always "jdbc")
```

| Database | JDBC URL Pattern |
|----------|------------------|
| MySQL | `jdbc:mysql://host:3306/dbname` |
| Oracle | `jdbc:oracle:thin:@host:1521:SID` |
| PostgreSQL | `jdbc:postgresql://host:5432/dbname` |
| SQLite | `jdbc:sqlite:filename.db` |

### Step 3: Create a Statement
A `Statement` is a channel through which SQL is sent to the DBMS.

```java
Statement stmt = con.createStatement();
PreparedStatement pstmt = con.prepareStatement(
    "INSERT INTO students(name, age) VALUES(?, ?)"
);
```

### Step 4: Execute the SQL Query
The `executeXxx()` method differs based on the SQL type:

| SQL Type | Method | Return Value |
|----------|--------|--------------|
| `SELECT` (Read) | `executeQuery(sql)` | `ResultSet` |
| `INSERT`, `UPDATE`, `DELETE` (Create/Update/Delete) | `executeUpdate(sql)` | `int` (row count) |
| DDL (`CREATE TABLE`, `DROP`) | `execute(sql)` | `boolean` |

### Step 5: Process Results and Close the Connection
Resources must always be closed to prevent **memory leaks** and **connection pool exhaustion**.

```java
ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery();
while (rs.next()) {
    System.out.println(rs.getString("name"));
}
con.close();  // Also closes Statement and ResultSet
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Best Practice (KTU Exam Favorite):** Use **try-with-resources** (Java SE 7+) to auto-close JDBC objects. This is the modern, KTU-preferred pattern.

## 2.2 Why `PreparedStatement` > `Statement`?

This is a **classic KTU question**. The reasons are:

1. **Pre-compilation:** SQL is compiled once at the database, then re-used with different parameters → **faster execution**.
2. **SQL Injection Prevention:** Parameters are bound separately, so malicious SQL like `' OR '1'='1` is treated as **data, not code**.
3. **Readability:** Placeholder `?` makes the SQL cleaner.
4. **Automatic Type Conversion:** Driver handles data type conversion (e.g., `Date`, `Timestamp`).
5. **Binary Data Support:** Can handle large objects like BLOB/CLOB using `setBinaryStream()`.

> [!NOTE]
> **SQL Injection Example (Why `Statement` is dangerous):**
> ```java
> // User input
> String user = "' OR '1'='1";
> // Vulnerable Statement
> Statement stmt = con.createStatement();
> ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery(
>     "SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '" + user + "'"
> );
> // Resulting SQL: SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '' OR '1'='1'
> // Returns ALL users!
> ```

## 2.3 ResultSet Navigation

A `ResultSet` cursor points to the current row. By default, it scrolls **forward only** and is **read-only**.

```java
// Default cursor — forward only
Statement stmt = con.createStatement();

// Scrollable + Updatable cursor
Statement stmt2 = con.createStatement(
    ResultSet.TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,
    ResultSet.CONCUR_UPDATABLE
);
```

**Key `ResultSet` Methods:**

| Method | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `rs.next()` | Moves cursor to next row; returns `false` after last row |
| `rs.previous()` | Moves cursor to previous row (scrollable RS only) |
| `rs.first()` / `rs.last()` | Jump to first / last row |
| `rs.absolute(int row)` | Jump to a specific row number |
| `rs.getInt("col")` | Read integer from column by name |
| `rs.getString(1)` | Read string from column 1 (1-indexed) |
| `rs.updateString("col", val)` | Update column value (updatable RS only) |
| `rs.updateRow()` | Push updates to DB (updatable RS only) |

## 2.4 Transaction Management (ACID)

JDBC supports **transactions** to ensure **Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability** (ACID properties).

```java
con.setAutoCommit(false);   // Begin transaction

try {
    // Execute multiple SQL statements
    pstmt1.executeUpdate();
    pstmt2.executeUpdate();

    con.commit();           // Make changes permanent
} catch (SQLException e) {
    con.rollback();         // Undo on error
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> By default, JDBC runs in **auto-commit mode** — each SQL statement is committed individually. For multi-statement operations, you **MUST** set `autoCommit = false`, otherwise partial failures will leave the database in an inconsistent state.

