1 student record(s) inserted.
ID    Name                Age   Course
------------------------------------------------
1     Arjun Kumar         21    CSE
2     Meera Nair          20    IT
1 student record(s) updated.
1 student record(s) deleted.
ID    Name                Age   Course
------------------------------------------------
1     Arjun Kumar         21    AIML
```

## 3.3 Step-by-Step Analysis: Why Each Line Matters

| Line | Why it matters (KTU Valuation Logic) |
|------|---------------------------------------|
| `Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver")` | Triggers the driver's `static` block, which calls `DriverManager.registerDriver()`. Worth **1 mark**. |
| `DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS)` | Returns a live `Connection` to the DB. The URL must match the vendor's protocol. Worth **1 mark**. |
| `con.prepareStatement(sql)` | Pre-compiles SQL at the DB; returns a `PreparedStatement`. The `?` are placeholders. Worth **2 marks**. |
| `pstmt.setString(1, name)` | Binds the parameter — **1-indexed**, not 0-indexed. A common mistake! |
| `pstmt.executeUpdate()` | Returns `int` (rows affected). Use this for **non-SELECT** statements. Worth **1 mark**. |
| `pstmt.executeQuery()` | Returns a `ResultSet`. Use this **only** for `SELECT`. Worth **1 mark**. |
| `try (Connection con = ...)` | try-with-resources. Auto-calls `con.close()` even if an exception is thrown. Worth **1 mark**. |
| `rs.next()` | Advances the cursor; returns `false` when no more rows. Initial cursor is **before the first row**. |

## 3.4 Analytical Matrix: `Statement` vs `PreparedStatement` vs `CallableStatement`

| Feature | Statement | PreparedStatement | CallableStatement |
|---------|-----------|-------------------|-------------------|
| Inherits from | — | `Statement` | `PreparedStatement` |
| SQL Compilation | Every execution | Pre-compiled once | Stored in DB |
| Parameter Binding | No (string concat) | Yes (`?` placeholders) | Yes (`?` placeholders) |
| SQL Injection Safe | ❌ No | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |
| Performance (repeated) | Slow | Fast | Fastest |
| Use Case | One-time DDL/DML | Repeated parameterized queries | Stored procedures |
| Method to call procedure | — | — | `{call proc_name(?, ?)}` |

## 3.5 Analytical Matrix: Type 1 vs Type 4 JDBC Driver

| Criterion | Type 1 (JDBC-ODBC Bridge) | Type 4 (Thin Driver) |
|-----------|---------------------------|----------------------|
| Pure Java | No (uses ODBC + native code) | Yes |
| Performance | Slow (multiple translations) | Fast (direct protocol) |
| Portability | Poor | Excellent |
| Installation Complexity | High (ODBC setup required) | Just add JAR to classpath |
| Currently Recommended | ❌ Removed in Java 8 | ✅ Industry Standard |
| Example | `sun.jdbc.odbc.JdbcOdbcDriver` | `com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver` |

## 3.6 Transaction Example with Rollback

```java
public void transferFunds(int fromAcc, int toAcc, double amount) 
        throws SQLException, ClassNotFoundException {

    Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

    try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(URL, USER, PASS)) {

        // Begin transaction
        con.setAutoCommit(false);

        try (PreparedStatement debit = con.prepareStatement(
                 "UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - ? WHERE id = ?");
             PreparedStatement credit = con.prepareStatement(
                 "UPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + ? WHERE id = ?")) {

            // Debit source
            debit.setDouble(1, amount);
            debit.setInt(2, fromAcc);
            int d = debit.executeUpdate();

            // Credit destination
            credit.setDouble(1, amount);
            credit.setInt(2, toAcc);
            int c = credit.executeUpdate();

            // Validate: both must affect 1 row each
            if (d == 1 && c == 1) {
                con.commit();
                System.out.println("Transfer successful.");
            } else {
                con.rollback();
                System.out.println("Transfer failed — rolled back.");
            }
        } catch (SQLException e) {
            con.rollback();   // Undo on any error
            throw e;
        }
    }
}
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Analytical Insight:** Notice the `if-else` validation. If the source account does not exist (`d == 0`) but the destination does, the credit would succeed and the debit would silently fail, corrupting data. The explicit validation ensures **atomicity**.

