#### Model Solution for (b) — 7 Marks

```java
import java.sql.*;

public class SelectHighScorers {
    public static void main(String[] args) 
            throws ClassNotFoundException, SQLException {

        // Step 1: Load driver (0.5 mark)
        Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

        // Step 2: Open connection using try-with-resources (1 mark)
        String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/school";
        try (Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, "root", "password");
             PreparedStatement pstmt = con.prepareStatement(
                 "SELECT id, name, marks FROM student WHERE marks > ?")) {

            // Step 3: Bind parameter (1 mark)
            pstmt.setInt(1, 50);

            // Step 4: Execute the SELECT (1 mark)
            try (ResultSet rs = pstmt.executeQuery()) {

                // Step 5: Process the ResultSet (2 marks)
                System.out.printf("%-10s %-20s %-10s%n", 
                                  "ID", "Name", "Marks");
                System.out.println("----------------------------------------");
                while (rs.next()) {
                    int id    = rs.getInt("id");
                    String nm = rs.getString("name");
                    int mk    = rs.getInt("marks");
                    System.out.printf("%-10d %-20s %-10d%n", 
                                      id, nm, mk);
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**
- `executeQuery()` returns a `ResultSet` — a cursor-based iterator over the result table.
- `rs.next()` moves the cursor row by row. Initially, the cursor is **before the first row**, so the first `next()` call positions it on row 1.
- All three resources (`Connection`, `PreparedStatement`, `ResultSet`) are auto-closed by the **try-with-resources** statement.

