## ⚠️ KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls

> [!WARNING]
> **Where Students Commonly Lose Marks in JDBC Questions:**
>
> 1. **Using `executeQuery()` for INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE** — This is a **fatal error**. `executeQuery()` is **only** for SELECT. Use `executeUpdate()` for all DML operations. *(−2 marks)*
> 2. **0-indexed placeholders** — Writing `pstmt.setString(0, name)` instead of `pstmt.setString(1, name)`. JDBC parameters are **1-indexed**, not 0-indexed. *(−1 mark)*
> 3. **Forgetting `con.close()`** — Failing to close the connection causes resource leaks. KTU prefers `try-with-resources` over `try-catch-finally`. *(−1 mark)*
> 4. **String concatenation in queries** — Using `Statement` with concatenated SQL makes the code vulnerable to SQL injection and earns **0 marks** for "best practice". Always use `PreparedStatement`. *(−1 to −2 marks)*
> 5. **Confusing `execute()` vs `executeQuery()` vs `executeUpdate()`** — `execute()` returns `boolean` (used for DDL like CREATE/DROP). `executeQuery()` returns `ResultSet`. `executeUpdate()` returns `int`.
> 6. **Not loading the driver explicitly** — In JDBC 4.0+ the driver is auto-loaded via SPI, but KTU expects `Class.forName(...)` to be shown in your code.
> 7. **Forgetting to register the JAR** — Students write perfect code but forget the MySQL connector JAR. The error is `ClassNotFoundException: com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver`.
> 8. **Wrong JDBC URL format** — Forgetting `://`, wrong port (MySQL = 3306, Oracle = 1521, PostgreSQL = 5432).

